
             Messages with Cause & Remedy for C5G Robot Controller


  513  0-INFO 


  514  0-INFO Request canceled 

       Cause:
         An I/O request was canceled, usually due to a reset issued by one
         of the programs. 

       Remedy:
         None. 


  515  0-INFO Channel id error 


  516  0-INFO Channel table full 

       Cause:
         There are too many devices and/or files being accessed at once. 

       Remedy:
         Decrease the number of simultaneous device and file open requests. 


  519  0-INFO 


  520  0-INFO I/O request timeout 

       Cause:
         An I/O operation did not complete in the allowable time. 

       Remedy:
         Determine the cause of the device failure and retry it. 


  521  0-INFO EOF detected 

       Cause:
         The referenced file is at its end. 

       Remedy:
         Close the file and reopen it. 


  522  0-INFO 


  523  0-INFO 


  525  0-INFO 


  526  0-INFO 


  527  0-INFO 


  531  0-INFO 


  534  0-INFO No read access 

       Cause:
         A read was attempted on a device or LUN that is for writing only. 

       Remedy:
         Correct the program. 


  535  0-INFO No write access 

       Cause:
         A write was attempted on a device or LUN that is for reading only. 

       Remedy:
         Correct the program. 


  541  0-INFO 


  576  0-INFO File already exists 

       Cause:
         A new file cannot be created because a file by the same name
         already exists. 

       Remedy:
         Change the new file name or delete the existing file. 


  577  0-INFO File does not exist 

       Cause:
         No file by the specified name exists. 

       Remedy:
         Specify only existing files for read, update, delete, rename, etc. 


  578  0-INFO No space for file 

       Cause:
         There is no room on the disk to create the new file. 

       Remedy:
         Delete some old or obsolete files to make room for new ones. 


  579  0-INFO Invalid file name 

       Cause:
         The file name is too long or contains invalid characters. 

       Remedy:
         Specify a correct file name. 


  581  0-INFO File already open 

       Cause:
         The referenced file is already opened by this program. 

       Remedy:
         Correct the program. 


  582  0-INFO Cannot delete file 

       Cause:
         The file cannot be deleted, probably because it is a read-only,
         hidden or system file. 

       Remedy:
         Change the file's attributes if it really should be deleted. 


  583  0-INFO File opened exclusively 

       Cause:
         The file cannot be opened because another program has opened it for
         exclusive access. 

       Remedy:
         Wait until the file has been closed by the other program. 


  584  0-INFO Not a file 


  585  0-INFO Not on same volume 


  587  0-INFO Directory not empty 


  588  0-INFO Name too long 


  589  0-INFO Unsupported file operation 


  590  0-INFO Volume not available 


  591  0-INFO Invalid number of bytes 


  592  0-INFO Illegal name 


  593  0-INFO Cannot delete root 


  594  0-INFO Root directory full 

       Cause:
         The root directory is full. This could either depend to the number
         of files present in the directory or to the lenght of their name. 

       Remedy:
         The use of sub-directories is recommended in order to avoid the
         filling of the main root. Files should be deleted permanently
         otherwise they are still maintained (for being eventually
         undeleted) although not viewed by default; use the Recycle bin menu
         from the File page of the TP or the FilerView/Deleted and
         FilerDelete/Cleanup from TP-INT page or SYS_CALL. 


  595  0-INFO No label 


  596  0-INFO No contiguous space 


  597  0-INFO File descriptor obsolete 


  598  0-INFO File deleted 


  599  0-INFO Write only 


  600  0-INFO Illegal path 


  601  0-INFO Access beyond end of file 


  602  0-INFO Directory read only 


  603  0-INFO Bad volume format 


  604  0-INFO Illegal cluster number 


  605  0-INFO Open file failed 

       Cause:
         Unable to open the specified file. 

       Remedy:
         Determine the name of the file and why it cannot be opened. 


  606  0-INFO Invalid I/O operation 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to perform some file I/O operation on a device
         that does not support it 

       Remedy:
         Try and determine what operation was being performed and verify
         that it can be performed on this device. 


  607  0-INFO Error during file I/O 

       Cause:
         The file I/O operation generated an error. 

       Remedy:
         Check whether the disk is full or write protected. 


  608  0-INFO Unknown environment variable 

       Cause:
         An environment variable is specified on the file but is unknown. 

       Remedy:
         Check the parameter specified as the environment variable.

 2300  0-INFO Incorrect number of parameters 

       Cause:
         The number of parameters specified when the error was raised is not
         equal to the number defined in the message. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the same number of parameters have been specified. 


 2301  0-INFO Incorrect format of parameters 

       Cause:
         The parameter format for the message is not all string. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure all parameters are off type string. 


 2302  0-INFO Invalid version of DLL 


 2303  0-INFO Remote route add %s successful performed 


 2304  0-INFO Remote route add %s failed. Error:%d 


 2305  0-INFO No interface specified 


 2306  0-INFO Not connected to controller 


 2307  0-INFO Remote Route Add not supported by controller version 


 2308  0-INFO CWD '%s'. Absolute:'%s' 


 2309  0-INFO End of file reached 


 2310  0-INFO Null schema pointer specified 


 2311  0-INFO No parameter name specified 


 2312  0-INFO Null parameter address pointer 


 2313  0-INFO No configuration file specified 

       Cause:
         The configuration file name was empty (contained only the
         terminating character).  All configuration filenames must begin
         with an alphabetic character and consist of only alphanumeric
         characters or the underscore character ('_'). 

       Remedy:
         Make sure all configuration filenames follow the format described
         above. 


 2314  0-INFO No default configuration file specified 


 2315  0-INFO No section name specified 


 2316  0-INFO No module ID specified 


 2317  0-INFO Parameter %s in schema has unknown type code 


 2318  0-INFO Parameter %s not found in schema 


 2319  0-INFO Parameter <ParamName> not found in configuration file 

       Cause:
         The parameter was not found in the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Some configuration parameters must exist in the configuration file.
         Check the documentation of the parameter and add it to the proper
         configuration file. 


 2320  0-INFO Module ID <ModuleId> not found in tmc.cfg 

       Cause:
         The module id was not found in tmc.cfg.  Each module must have a
         section in this file which describes its particular configuration
         (configuration filename, executable filename, module id, etc.). 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the tmc.cfg file has the module id specified in one of
         the sections. 


 2321  0-INFO Section <ConfigSection> not found in configuration file 

       Cause:
         The section was not found in the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the configuration file being read has the proper section
         names and parameters in those sections. 


 2322  0-INFO Unexpected token found in configuration file 

       Cause:
         An unexpected token was found while reading the configuration file.
         This is caused by a syntax error in the file (like too many
         elements of an array, etc.). 

       Remedy:
         This is usually caused by the wrong number of elements in an array.
         Check all arrays first then check the syntax of the other elements
         of the configuration file. 


 2323  0-INFO Value for parameter <ParamName> is out of range 

       Cause:
         The value for the parameter in the configuration file is out of the
         valid range. 

       Remedy:
         Check the parameter documentation and make sure the value is within
         the allowed range. 


 2324  0-INFO Default value for parameter %s in schema is out of range 


 2325  0-INFO Module parameters out of range 

       Cause:
         The parameters for a module are out of range.  Either the module ID
         is out of range or the platform identifier is invalid. 

       Remedy:
         Consult the documentation for these parameters and correct the
         configuration file. 


 2326  0-INFO Parameter %s in schema has invalid (zero) string size 


 2327  0-INFO Error scanning for next token in configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred scanning for the next token in the configuration
         file. 

       Remedy:
         Check the parameter and value format for the entries of the
         configuration file. 


 2328  0-INFO Error closing configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred closing the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Note all circumstances causing the error and contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2329  0-INFO Error reading from configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred reading from the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Note all circumstances causing the error and contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2330  0-INFO Parameter <ParamName> doesn't have enough elements 

       Cause:
         The array parameter does not have enough elements. 

       Remedy:
         Check the documentation for the parameter and correct the
         configuration file. 


 2331  0-INFO Parameter <ParamName> has an invalid value 

       Cause:
         The parameter has an invalid value (integer value specified for a
         string type parameter, etc.). 

       Remedy:
         Consult the documentation for the parameter and correct the
         configuration file. 


 2332  0-INFO Fatal error reading configuration file 

       Cause:
         A fatal error was detected reading the configuration file.  Check
         the previous error for more specific information about the cause of
         the error. 

       Remedy:
         Check the previous errors and make corrections to the configuration
         file. 


 2333  0-INFO Invalid event type passed to ibfm_GetEventDest 

       Cause:
         An invalid event type value was passed to the functions
         ibfm_GBetEventDest. 

       Remedy:
         Verify the event type argument in the call to ibfm_GBetEventDest. 


 2334  0-INFO The Controllers key does not exist in the system registry 

       Cause:
         The software is not properly installed. 

       Remedy:
         Reinstall the software from the install disks. 


 2335  0-INFO The controller is not registered 

       Cause:
         The controller being connected is not registered with the PC.  This
         can happen if the software is not properly installed or the
         controller has not yet checked in with the PC. 

       Remedy:
         Properly install the software.  If the problem still exists, call
         customer support. 


 2336  0-INFO Controller network address not specified 

       Cause:
         The network address of the controller is not registered.  This can
         happen if the software is not properly installed or the controller
         has not yet checked in with the PC. 

       Remedy:
         Properly install the software.  If the problem still exists, call
         customer support. 


 2337  0-INFO Invalid controller network address 

       Cause:
         The controller network address is not valid. 

       Remedy:
         Note all circumstances causing the error and contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2338  0-INFO Last controller not specified 

       Cause:
         The last controller connected to was not specified.  This can
         happen if the software is not properly installed or the controller
         has not yet checked in with the PC. 

       Remedy:
         If the application allows, connect to a controller via the Connect
         menu. If the application does not allow you to connect, contact
         COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2339  0-INFO Application not registered 

       Cause:
         The application is not registered.  This can happen if the software
         is not properly installed or the applications version is not
         correct. 

       Remedy:
         Properly install the software.  If the problem still exists,
         contact COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2340  0-INFO Error writing to configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred while writing to the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Check available disk space. Contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2341  0-INFO Error deleting old configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred while replacing to the configuration file. 

       Remedy:
         Check file attributes on configuration file. Contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2342  0-INFO Error replacing configuration file 

       Cause:
         An error occurred while replacing the old configuration file with
         the new one. 

       Remedy:
         Contact COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com). 


 2343  0-INFO Parameter <ParamName> is required therefore does not need a
       default 

       Cause:
         The parameter's Scope flag in the schema indicates that it is
         required in the config file (Scope's 3rd bit is "1").  Therefore,
         the default value in the schema is never used.  Instead, a value is
         always read from the config file. 

       Remedy:
         The default value should be replaced by a NULL or the 3rd bit of
         the Scope flag should be set to "0". 


 2344  0-INFO Parameter <ParamName> not found in section <SectionName> of
       configuration file <FileName> 

       Cause:
         Some configuration parameters must exist in the configuration file.
         This error occurs when one of these parameters was not found in the
         configuration file.  The parameter name, the section name, and file
         name are supplied so you know where the parameter belongs. 

       Remedy:
         Check the documentation of the parameter and add it to the proper
         configuration file in the proper section. 


 2345  0-INFO Previous error occurred on line <LineNumber> in section
       <SectionName> of configuration file <FileName> 

       Cause:
         This error simply reports additional information for the previously
         reported error related to the configuration files.  The information
         provided includes the line number, the section name, and file name
         so you know where the error was detected. 

       Remedy:
         Check the previously reported error and use the information in this
         error to help you locate the problem.

 8193  2-WARNING <string> 

       Cause:
         This message, concerning the handling of devices on the Powerlink
         network, either highlights a critical aspect or represents an
         informational. If strings similar to SL1.IF2.STxxx (xxx is a
         number) are present, it is needed to focus the attention on
         Powerlink. The device can be an ACOPOS, a Bus Coupler or a Safe
         Logic and the problem could be its lack on the Powerlink, although
         correctly configured. In case 'epl_any' string is indicated, the
         subject is an ACOPOS module. Please note that the ACOPOS address on
         rotational commutators is expressed in hexadecimal notation, while
         the address 'xxx' is expressed in decimal notation. The system also
         reports the informational on the performed updates on the
         interested devices. For example: "Module (epl_any) not found on
         Path: SL1.IF2.ST19", means that the ACOPOS device at address 19 in
         decimal is absent on the Powerlink network. 

       Remedy:
         Please follow the chain of connections up to the device which
         address is the reported one. 


 8194  11-DRIVE OFF EPLInit failure %d 


 8195  11-DRIVE OFF EPLCreate Environment failure <error> 

       Cause:
         This error occurs when one or more devices are absent on the
         Powerlink network. 

       Remedy:
         Please check if other messages are previously shown which could
         help in identifying the device which is absent on the Powerlink
         network. The device and its address are indicated by strings
         similar to SL1.IF2.STxxx, where xxx is the address. 


 8196  11-DRIVE OFF Register NG Call Back failure %d 


 8197  11-DRIVE OFF Create Device failure. Interface <path_string> Error
       <error> 

       Cause:
         This error occurs when one or more devices are absent on the
         Powerlink network. The indicated interface, like 'SL1.IF2',
         identifies the main Powerlink network; 'SL2.IF1' identifies the
         network of the Powerlink annex. 

       Remedy:
         Please check if other messages are previously shown which could
         help in identifying the device which is absent on the Powerlink
         network. The device and its address are indicated by strings
         similar to SL1.IF2.STxxx, where xxx is the address. 


 8198  11-DRIVE OFF Interrupt connect failure %d 


 8199  11-DRIVE OFF EPLCFG.XML not found 

       Cause:
         The configuration file EPL_CFG.XML has not been found. 

       Remedy:
         Please install a backup copy of the file o regenerate the file. 


 8200  10-DRIVE OFF Firmware-FPGA loaded: shutdown is required 

       Cause:
         The firmware has been loaded on FPGA board. 

       Remedy:
         It is needed to switch the controller off and on in order to force
         a cold restart. 


 8201  11-DRIVE OFF Open Device failure. Interface <path_string> Cyclic
       <cyclic_string> Code <code_error> 

       Cause:
         One or more devices could be absent on the Powerlink network.
         Please check if other messages are previously shown which could
         help in identifying the device which is absent on the Powerlink
         network. In this situation the Powerlink network does not properly
         work. If the Cyclic parameter reports 'Y', it means that the
         scanning of the devices on the Powerlink network has not been
         activated. The indicated interface, like 'SL1.IF2' for the main
         Powerlink or 'SL2.IF1' for the Powerlink annex, identifies the
         Powerlink network which could not be activated. 

       Remedy:
         Please check that all devices configured on the Powerlink network
         are physically connected. Please check if other messages are
         previously shown which could help in identifying the device which
         is absent on the Powerlink network. The device and its address are
         indicated by strings similar to SL1.IF2.STxxx, where xxx is the
         address. 


 8202  10-DRIVE OFF Device address out of range 


 8203  10-DRIVE OFF EPL environment not initialized 


 8204  8-HOLD Fieldbus service %d failure %d Par %d

 8206  2-WARNING [%s,%d] 


 8207  2-WARNING [%s,%d] %d 


 8208  2-WARNING [%s,%d] %d %d 


 8209  2-WARNING RS (0x1C717) workspace exceeded from link: %d 


 8210  2-WARNING RS (0x1C717) workspace exceeded: %d 


 8211  2-WARNING RS (0x1C717) info0: <info0> - info1: <info1> 

       Cause:
         Info0 = Reason (0xnn = instance number of block type) Info1 =
         Additional information Reason 0xnn01: Limit of angles in
         user-defined units exceeded (Info1: Space_ID) Reason 0xnn02: Change
         of TableID during operation recognized (Info1: TableID) Reason
         0xnn03: Change of position tolerance (S_PositionTolerance) during
         operation recognized Reason 0xnn04: Negative position tolerance
         (S_PositionToleracne) defined Reason 0xnn05: Invalid position data
         Reason 0xnn06: Object with KinObject_ID exceeded a defined safe- or
         workspace (Info1: KinObject_ID) Reason 0xnn07: An object of the
         mechanical system exceeded a defined safe- or workspace  (Info1:
         Space_ID) Reason 0xnn08: Invalid value connected with input
         S_Activate_BrakingDistance Reason 0xnn09: Change of braking
         activation (S_Activate_BrakingDistance) during operation recognized
         Reason 0xnn0A: Dimensions of defined space too small (Info1:
         Space_ID) Reason 0xnn0B: Current braking distance of object
         (KinObject_ID) in WS (Space_ID) too high (thrown twice) (Info1: 1.
         KinObject_ID, 2. Space_ID) Reason 0xnn0C: Braking distance
         calculation can not be performed because parameters of deceleration
         ramp are not available Reason 0xnnF7: internal error Reason 0xnnF8:
         Data of handle (index) are invalid - access not possible (Info1:
         index of wrong handle) Reason 0xnnF9: Used tool (Info1) does not
         exist (Info1: ToolID (1-4)) Reason 0xnnFA: internal error Reason
         0xnnFB: Handle in NOT_DEFINED-state (Info1: index of wrong handle)
         Reason 0xnnFC: Maximal number of block instances exceeded (Info1:
         number of instances) Reason 0xnnFD: Handle in error-state or
         invalid address (Info1: index of wrong handle) Reason 0xnnFE:
         Forbidden change of handle (Info1: index of wrong handle) Reason
         0xnnFF: Handle of a wrong block type connected (Info1: index of
         wrong handle)

10781  0-INFO Monitor enable limit reached 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to enable a monitor when too many are already
         enabled. 

       Remedy:
         Disable some monitors. 


10782  0-INFO Illegal method call over the Comau data connection 


10783  0-INFO The specified port is out of range 

       Cause:
         The port index specified is either smaller than 1 or larger than
         the maximum port index. 

       Remedy:
         Index ports within range. 


10784  0-INFO Hard-soft status error 

       Cause:
         Both hard and soft errors are both zero. 

       Remedy:
         Hard and soft errors should have one or both errors non-zero.
         Ensure that this is the case! 


10785  0-INFO Routine not found 

       Cause:
         The RE requested could not be found. 

       Remedy:
         Verify the name of the RE (routine) that is being requested. 


10786  0-INFO Bad event type specified 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to define an event with a bad type. 

       Remedy:
         Check the type of event being created. 


10787  0-INFO Invalid statement request 

       Cause:
         The requested statement is not supported over the Comau data
         connection or invalid arguments passed. 

       Remedy:
         Verify how and which statement is being called. 


10788  0-INFO Bad array range extent 

       Cause:
         The array range requested specified an extent that is too large or
         too small. 

       Remedy:
         Never use array range extents of zero. 


10789  0-INFO Alarm message overflow 

       Cause:
         The alarm buffer has overflowed so some alarm messages may be lost. 

       Remedy:
         Use alternative command to see alarms or increase size of buffer
         (see $REM_TUNE). 


10790  0-INFO Edit server session specified was not open 

       Cause:
         The specified edit server session was not open. 

       Remedy:
         Open an edit server session first, before trying to use it. 


10791  0-INFO Edit server session out of range 

       Cause:
         A bogus value for the edit server session id was received. 

       Remedy:
         Close the edit session and re-open. 


10792  0-INFO Too many open edit server sessions 

       Cause:
         The limit for concurrently open edit server sessions has been
         reached. 

       Remedy:
         Close some unneeded edit session first. 


10793  0-INFO Server already executing a command 

       Cause:
         Only a single command can be executed at a time. 

       Remedy:
         Wait until the command has completed by issuing synchronously 


10794  0-INFO Invalid port 

       Cause:
         Invalid port specified. 

       Remedy:
         Specify a valid port. 


10795  0-INFO Array too large 

       Cause:
         The array is too large, the current limit for a 1-D array is 65535
         elements and for a 2-D array is 2147483648 elements. 

       Remedy:
         Decrease the size of the array. 


10796  0-INFO Insufficient rights 

       Cause:
         The requested operation could not be performed as client has
         insufficient rights. 

       Remedy:
         Login as a user with sufficient rights. 


10797  0-INFO Uninitialised data 

       Cause:
         The variable obtained is not yet initialised. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the variable is set. 


10798  0-INFO No such monitor 

       Cause:
         A search for a monitor failed. 

       Remedy:
         Check the identifier of the monitor being searched. 


10799  0-INFO No action defined 

       Cause:
         An operation has been requested on an action set that does not
         exists. 

       Remedy:
         Check the transaction id used. 


10800  0-INFO Bad transition identifier 

       Cause:
         The transaction id associated with the action set is invalid. 

       Remedy:
         Check the value supplied as the transaction id. 


10801  0-INFO Action already existing 

       Cause:
         A new action set is being defined but it already exists. 

       Remedy:
         Check duplicate transaction ids. 


10802  0-INFO Action not correct 

       Cause:
         The action requested to be performed is invalid. 

       Remedy:
         Supply the correct values for the action set. 


10803  0-INFO Action definition error 


10804  0-INFO Set uninit error 

       Cause:
         Attempted to set a value to uninit. 

       Remedy:
         Always set a value to a valid value. 


10805  0-INFO Arm number did not match 

       Cause:
         Specified an incorrect arm number. 

       Remedy:
         Specify a correct arm number. 


10806  0-INFO The connection to the Comau controller has died 

       Cause:
         Comau controller's server or network has gone down. 

       Remedy:
         Confirm Comau controller is running and with no fatal errors and
         reconnect. 


10807  0-INFO Comau controller not found 

       Cause:
         A connection to the specified Comau controller could not be
         established. 

       Remedy:
         Specify a valid Comau controller IP name/address. 


10808  0-INFO The IPCB variable was not found 

       Cause:
         A symbolic lookup of an IPCB variable failed (IPCB was present). 

       Remedy:
         Specify a valid stack varaible name. 


10809  0-INFO The IPCB variable was found, but with no data 

       Cause:
         A symbolic lookup of an IPCB variable failed (IPCB and variable
         were present) but the variable contained no data and was not a
         stack variable. 

       Remedy:
         Check class and name of variable being obtained. 


10810  0-INFO The client has performed a disconnect 


10811  0-INFO Open executed before insertion in the group 

       Cause:
         The monitoring has been added to a group before having been opened. 

       Remedy:
         Open a monitoring or an event before adding it to a group. 


10812  0-INFO No internal locks left 


10813  0-INFO Could not lock as in power failure 


10814  0-INFO Could not lock as in power failure 


10815  0-INFO Command cannot be issued 

       Cause:
         A command cannot be issued as the command system is not running. 

       Remedy:
         This is probably due to Fatal error. Restart the Comau controller. 


10816  0-INFO The program entry cound not be found 

       Cause:
         The program was not loaded into memory or running. 

       Remedy:
         Load the program or start executing it. 


10817  0-INFO Log message overflow 

       Cause:
         The log message buffer has overflowed so some log messages messages
         may be lost. 

       Remedy:
         Use alternative command to see log messages or increase size of
         buffer (see $REM_TUNE). 


10818  0-INFO The Monitor/Alarm/Event or Log Message was not open 

       Cause:
         The particular server to client messaging channel was not open when
         an action was performed on it. 

       Remedy:
         Open the server to client messaging channel first. 


10819  0-INFO User not logged in 

       Cause:
         The startup ID can only be set after a user manually logs in. 

       Remedy:
         Manually login first. 


10820  0-INFO Attempting to set variable to uninit value 

       Cause:
         A value sent from the client and used to set the value of a
         variable was UNINIT. 

       Remedy:
         Set variables only with values that are not UNINIT. 


10821  0-INFO Program/Variable being monitored has been deleted 

       Cause:
         The program or variable being monitored has been deleted. 

       Remedy:
         Close down the monitor is the only solution & requirement. 


10822  0-INFO Cannot perform operation on dead monitor 

       Cause:
         The monitor has failed for some previous reason and therefore
         actions cannot be performed on it. 

       Remedy:
         Do not perform operations on "dead" monitors. 


10823  0-INFO Invalid Fixed monitor on a program entry 

       Cause:
         The monitor has been defined with a FIXED attribute but this is not
         allowed when it refers to a program entry. 

       Remedy:
         Define the monitor without the FIX attribute and handle program
         erase. 


10824  0-INFO No monitor variable-programs lock available 

       Cause:
         An attempt to create a monitor failed as there are no more locks on
         variables/programs available. 

       Remedy:
         Increase the number of available locks (see $REM_TUNE). 


10825  0-INFO LUN already open 

       Cause:
         The file handle is already in use on an open file. 

       Remedy:
         Close the file and then re-issue the open. 


10826  0-INFO LUN not open 

       Cause:
         Operation attempted with no controller file, pipe or device open. 

       Remedy:
         Call open before any other I/O operation. 


10827  0-INFO No available VP2 screen space 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to create a new screen VP2_SCRN_CREATE and
         there is no available space. 

       Remedy:
         At the moment, there is a limit of number of VP2 Screens that can
         be created. Check that this limit has not been exceeded. 


10828  0-INFO No available VP2 component space 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to add a new component VP2_ADD and there is no
         available space. 

       Remedy:
         At the moment, there is a limit of number of VP2 components that
         can be created. Check that this limit has not been exceeded. 


10829  4-PAUSE Cannot VP2 add to oneself 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to VP2_ADD a component to itself. 

       Remedy:
         Please check what you are doing and try not to add a component to
         itself. 


10830  4-PAUSE Component already added 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to VP2_ADD a component to itself. 

       Remedy:
         Please check what you are doing and try not to add a component to
         itself. 


10831  4-PAUSE Program already has a VP2 screen 

       Cause:
         One program can only create one screen. 

       Remedy:
         Check that another screen has not been created. If necessary run
         from different programs. 


10832  4-PAUSE VP2 component not added 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to perform an operation eg. VP2_UPDATE on a
         component that has not yet been added to the program. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component has been added by this program. 


10833  4-PAUSE VP2_UPDATE bad parameter 

       Cause:
         Bad paramater passed to VP2_UPDATE. 

       Remedy:
         Check what is being passed to VP2_UPDATE. 


10834  4-PAUSE VP2_ADD component's parent/screen added by different
       program 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to VP2_ADD a component to a parent or screen
         added by a different executing program or there is no screen added. 

       Remedy:
         Check that both the child and parent component are added by the
         same executing program Make sure that VP2_SCRN_CREATE is first. 


10835  4-PAUSE VP2_ADD component's already added 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to VP2_ADD a component when the component has
         already been VP2_ADDed to a different component. 

       Remedy:
         Check if the component has been added and if so remove it. 


10836  4-PAUSE Session-screen limit reached 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to open a screen and the limit of screens per
         session has been reached. 

       Remedy:
         There is a current restriction on the number of screens that can be
         opened per session. 


10837  4-PAUSE VP2 Screen already being shown 

       Cause:
         A VP2 screen can only be shown by one remote session. 

       Remedy:
         Check who is displaying this screen and decide who can show it. 


10838  4-PAUSE No such VP2 screen 

       Cause:
         A VP2 screen does not exist. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the screen exists. 


10839  0-INFO VP2 Screen not opened 

       Cause:
         A VP2 screen is not opened. 

       Remedy:
         Attempt to close a screen that is not opened by this session. 


10840  0-INFO No VP2 screen found 

       Cause:
         Attempt to get a screen. 

       Remedy:
         It appears that no screens have been defined. Make sure that
         VP2_SCRN_CREATE has been issued by this program. 


10841  0-INFO Circular add of components 

       Cause:
         VP2_ADD is being called but the components are being recursively
         configured that is the parent and child are in some way related. 

       Remedy:
         Review how the VP2_ADD is being called. 


10842  0-INFO Too many sub menus added to a menu 

       Cause:
         At time of writing VP2 menus can only support a single submenu per
         menu item. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure only no submenus are added to a submenu. 


10843  0-INFO Container cannot be set focus 

       Cause:
         A focus gained event was called on a container. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that there are no focusable fields in the record definitions
         of new containers. 


10844  0-INFO A non-tabsheet was added to a tabpane 

       Cause:
         Something other than a vp2tabsheet is being VP2_ADD'd to a tabpane. 

       Remedy:
         Do not add any other component to a tabpane different than a
         tabsheet. 


10845  0-INFO Tabsheet limit reached 

       Cause:
         Too many tabsheets have tried to be added to the tabpane. 

       Remedy:
         Remove one or more tabsheets from the VP2_ADD statement to the
         tabpane. 


10846  0-INFO Unable to write to the pipe 

       Cause:
         The pipe has not been specified or was not created properly. 

       Remedy:
         Specify a pipe or ensure that one has been created. 


10847  0-INFO The requested system color is invalid 

       Cause:
         THe requested system color number is outside of the range
         available. 

       Remedy:
         Change the system color required. 


10848  0-INFO The specified class was not found 

       Cause:
         The class specified was not found in the distribution. 

       Remedy:
         Check spelling of class, ensure class is available on the
         classpath. 


10849  0-INFO Image is not on classpath 

       Cause:
         The image is not available on the classpath. 

       Remedy:
         PLace the image required onto into a folder on the classpath. 


10850  0-INFO The specified menu type does not exist 

       Cause:
         The type of menu specified in attr_func does not exist. 

       Remedy:
         Change the menu type. 


10851  0-INFO Could not add component 

       Cause:
         Either the class does not exist or is not valid for this instance. 

       Remedy:
         Check the class version and that it is located on the classpath. 


10852  0-INFO The pipe name supplied is invalid or null 

       Cause:
         When trying to open a pipe, the pipe name supplied is null. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure the pipe name is specified. 


10853  0-INFO The pipe was unable to be created 

       Cause:
         The pipe create method returned an error. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure the pipe name is valid and network connections are present. 


10854  0-INFO Error sending event to program entry 

       Cause:
         The send error event for the program entry returned an error. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure a valid program is running on the controller. 


10855  0-INFO Error sending event to controller 

       Cause:
         The send system error method returned an error. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure the controller is still connected and network connection is
         working and that you have appropriate priviledges. 


10856  0-INFO Screen already added 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to add a screen VP2_SCRN_ADD when the screen
         has already been added to a different device. 

       Remedy:
         Issue VP2_SCRN_REMOVE to remove from other device. 


10857  0-INFO Screen remove failed 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to remove a screen VP2_SCRN_REMOVE when either
         it has not already been added or the screen is not owned by this
         program. 

       Remedy:
         Check whether the screen has been added and that the screen was
         created by this program. 


10858  0-INFO Invalid screen id 

       Cause:
         A screen identifier is being used and it is an invalid number. 

       Remedy:
         Check the screen identifier being used. 


10859  0-INFO Bad screen operation 

       Cause:
         An operation was being attempted on a screen that is invalid. 

       Remedy:
         Check the screen identifier being used and the operation. 


10860  0-INFO Invalid physical device identifier 

       Cause:
         A physical device identifier is invalid. 

       Remedy:
         Check the parameter pass to the routine. 


10861  0-INFO Screen not available 

       Cause:
         The requested screen is no longer available. 

       Remedy:
         Since the list was displayed and making the request the screen has
         been taken by someone else. 


10862  0-INFO Incorrect type added to menubar 

       Cause:
         Something other than a menu was trying to be added to menubar. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure only vp2menu types are being added to vp2menubar. 


10863  0-INFO Unable to add menu to item 

       Cause:
         A menu item or menu was trying to be added to a menu item. 

       Remedy:
         Change the type of menu to something other than vp2_term before
         adding to it. 


10864  0-INFO Could not add component to menu 

       Cause:
         Something other than a vp2menu is trying to be added to a menu. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the add of other components to menus. 


10865  0-INFO Unable to add menu to container 

       Cause:
         The current version of VP2 does not support adding menus to all
         containers. 

       Remedy:
         Add menus to menubars only. 


10866  0-INFO Error removing component 

       Cause:
         Unable to remove component. 

       Remedy:
         Check component still exists. 


10867  0-INFO Menu ordinal is too high 

       Cause:
         Value in ordinal field is greater than the number of positions
         available. 

       Remedy:
         Change the ordinal of this menu. 


10868  0-INFO Menu not found 

       Cause:
         Menu has not been added or created. 

       Remedy:
         Add menu to menubar. 


10869  0-INFO Menu has already been added 

       Cause:
         This menu has already been added. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the add statement that adds this menu again. 


10870  0-INFO First focus not found 

       Cause:
         The id of the first focusable component was not found. 

       Remedy:
         Check the id in the first_fcs field for this component. 


10871  0-INFO Cannot remove a system screen 

       Cause:
         For the moment it is not possible to remove a system screen. 

       Remedy:
         Do not remove a system screen using a VP2 builtin routine. 


10872  0-INFO Cannot add a system screen 

       Cause:
         For the moment it is not possible to add a system screen. 

       Remedy:
         Do not add a system screen using a VP2 builtin routine. 


10873  0-INFO Not possible to get a system screen 

       Cause:
         For the moment it is not possible to get a system screen. 

       Remedy:
         Do not get a system screen using a VP2 builtin. 


10874  0-INFO System screen cannot be made available 

       Cause:
         For the moment it is not possible to make a system screen
         available. 

       Remedy:
         Do not make a system screen available using a VP2 builtin routine. 


10875  0-INFO No VP2 user screen type found 

       Cause:
         The VP2 screen record could not be found, the program may have been
         deactivated or memory erased. 

       Remedy:
         Do not deactivate the VP2 program or perform a memory erase. 


10876  0-INFO Must add screen to left menu or setup 

       Cause:
         The VP2 screen added was not deemed to be for the left menu or the
         setup page. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that the position field in the screen record are set
         correctly, could be uninit. 


10877  0-INFO Must add screen before removing 

       Cause:
         The VP2 screen could not be removed because it was never added. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that VP2 screens are added before they are removed. 


10878  0-INFO Cannot get a user screen 

       Cause:
         Getting the user screen currently displayed is not supported at the
         moment. 

       Remedy:
         Do not issue this VP2 builtin routine. 


10879  0-INFO Screen already added 

       Cause:
         Cannot add screen when another already added. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure no screens are added before performing add. 


10880  0-INFO VP2 session shutdown 

       Cause:
         Whilst issuing a request the VP2 session shutdown. 

       Remedy:
         If you can expect this then issue ERR_TRAP_ON on the VP2 generic
         error 40089. 


10881  0-INFO No TP session found 

       Cause:
         A VP2 request was made to the physical device PDV_TP but there is
         no such connection. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the TP is connected. 


10882  0-INFO Component cannot have _ at start 

       Cause:
         A component name has been specified with an '_' at the start. 

       Remedy:
         Rename the record moving the '_' to the end. 


10883  0-INFO Cannot add setup page 

       Cause:
         Current release does not support adding setup pages. 

       Remedy:
         Add left menu pages only. 


10884  0-INFO Cannot add component to component 

       Cause:
         A component was added to another component. 

       Remedy:
         Do not try to add a component to a component. 


10885  0-INFO Cannot open screen lun 

       Cause:
         The lun specified in the VP2 Screen component failed to open. 

       Remedy:
         Check the lun_name field in the screen record. 


10886  0-INFO Cannot find component for VP2_SEL_SET 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to set the focus or chooser to a component that
         cannot be found. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component has been added to the screen. 


10887  0-INFO No matching screen ordinal 

       Cause:
         The specified ordinal in the VP2 screen could not be found. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the VP2 pages can accept the specified ordinal number. 


10888  0-INFO Value out of bounds 

       Cause:
         The entered value does not fall inside of specified bounds. 

       Remedy:
         Re-enter the number or change the bounds. 


10889  0-INFO Cannot find comp 

       Cause:
         The specified component could not be found in the list of
         components added to the screen. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component has been added and is owned by this
         program. 


10890  0-INFO Component could not be found for delete 

       Cause:
         The specified component could not be found in the list of
         components added to the screen when attempting to delete it. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component has been added and is owned by this
         program. 


10891  0-INFO Component could not be updated 

       Cause:
         The specified component could not be found in the list of
         components added to the screen when attempting to update the list. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component has been added and is owned by this
         program. 


10892  0-INFO VP2_REMOVE on screen component 

       Cause:
         One cannot issue a VP2_REMOVE on the screen component. 

       Remedy:
         If you wish to remove the screen use VP2_SCRN_REMOVE. 


10893  0-INFO Error setting the field value 

       Cause:
         There was a problem updating the value of a field for this
         component. 

       Remedy:
         If this is a text entry component, make sure that the string field
         is large enough to take the value that has been set. 


10894  0-INFO Screen already added 

       Cause:
         The screen could not be added as it was already added. 

       Remedy:
         Do not added a VP2 screen more than once to the same display
         device. 


10895  0-INFO The specified image could not be found 

       Cause:
         The image that was associated with the component could not be found
         on the VP2 display device. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that the image(s) are available to the VP2 display device. 


10896  0-INFO A message bar was already visible 

       Cause:
         VP2 was directed to display a message bar when one was already
         being displayed. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that VP2 is directed to display a message bar one at a time. 


10897  0-INFO VP2 performed a VP2 add on a screen with ordinal < 0 

       Cause:
         VP2_ADD only works with screens with ordinals >0. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that VP2_SCRN_ADD is used with screen with ordinals >0. 


10898  0-INFO VP2 attempted to remove a screen that was not found 

       Cause:
         A VP2 program has removed a screen that was not known to VP2. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that VP2_ADD/VP2_AVAIL is performed first. 


10899  0-INFO VP2 attempted to make available a user screen 

       Cause:
         VP2 cannot make a user screen (ordinal >0) available. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that user screen is used with VP2_SCRN_ADD/VP2_SCRN_REMOVE
         not VP2_SCRN_AVAIL/VP2_SCRN_UNAVAIL. 


10900  0-INFO VP2 attempted to make a user screen unavailable 

       Cause:
         VP2 cannot make a user screen (ordinal >0) unavailable. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that user screen is used with VP2_SCRN_ADD/VP2_SCRN_REMOVE
         not VP2_SCRN_AVAIL/VP2_SCRN_UNAVAIL. 


10901  0-INFO VP2 cannot find the screen specified used in VP2_SCRN_SET 

       Cause:
         The screen specified in the arguments of VP2_SCRN_SET could not be
         found. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that the specified screen has been added to the correct
         display device before using VP2_SCRN_SET. 


10902  0-INFO VP2_SCRN_GET not implemented yet 

       Cause:
         Called builtin VP2_SCRN_GET or VP2_SEL_GET. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use VP2_SCRN_GET or VP2_SET_GET. 


10903  0-INFO Too many VP2 setup screens have been made available 

       Cause:
         The maximum number of setup screens that can be present has been
         exceeded. 

       Remedy:
         Do not make so many vp2 setup screens available. 


10904  0-INFO The vp2 setup screen specified could not be found 

       Cause:
         The vp2 setup screen specified for making unavailable could not be
         found. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that the VP2_SCRN_AVAIL builtin completes successfully
         before attempting a VP2_SCRN_UNAVAIL. 


10905  0-INFO A dimension of a component/container is less than -1 

       Cause:
         It is not possible to specify a dimension of a component to be less
         than -1. 

       Remedy:
         Ensure that components have positive dimensions or -1 for inherit
         dimension from parent. 


10906  0-INFO VP2 Frame session is not unique 

       Cause:
         The VP2Frame session started is not unique and clashes with an
         existing session connected to this controller. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the same VP2Frame has not been started from the same
         remote device. If necessary change the session name. 


10907  0-INFO Screen has been closed/deleted 

       Cause:
         An attempt has been to perform an operation on a screen that has
         been deleted. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the screen exists. 


10908  0-INFO VP2Frames not licensed 

       Cause:
         An attempt has been to using VP2.Frames and not licensed. 

       Remedy:
         Purchase the license. 


10909  0-INFO Error refreshing VP2Table 

       Cause:
         A problem was found refreshing the VP2Table component 

       Remedy:
         Check the contents of the VP2Table. 


10910  0-INFO Component not found 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to reference a component but this component
         does not exist on the screen 

       Remedy:
         Check that the component does exist on the specified screen /
         program 


10911  0-INFO Invalid VPS/VTR/CIO contents 

       Cause:
         The load of the VPS/VTR/CIO file failed due to some invalid
         contents in the file 

       Remedy:
         Check that the file is a correct VPS/VTR/CIO file and not something
         else otherwise send the file to Comau to be controlled. 


10912  0-INFO Cannot add to VP2 array component 

       Cause:
         A VP2 component cannot be added to a VP2 array component/container. 

       Remedy:
         Use single elements for the container as opposed to array 


10913  0-INFO VP2 screen not found 

       Cause:
         An attempt to operate on a screen but the screen either does not
         exist or is not being displayed. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the screen exists and is being displayed. 


10914  0-INFO VP2_SEL_SET index out of bounds 

       Cause:
         The index passed to the VP2_SEL_SET is out of the foreseen bounds. 

       Remedy:
         Specified a number include in the proper range. 


10915  0-INFO Missing parent field name in vp2datalink data field 

       Cause:
         The data field of the vp2datalink contains a string that is not the
         name of one of the fields of the component to which the datalink is
         added. 

       Remedy:
         Change the contents of the data field to either an empty string or
         the name of one of the fields of the component to which the
         datalink is added. 


10916  0-INFO Type not correct for vp2variant 

       Cause:
         The component field of the vp2variant contains the name of an
         internal vp2engine component which cannot be used with vp2variant. 

       Remedy:
         Change the contents of the component field to the name of any
         publicly accessible VP2 component except vp2datalink or vp2variant. 


10917  0-INFO Data link index out of bounds 

       Cause:
         The idx1 or idx2 fields of the datalink contain a value that is
         less than 1 or greater than corresponding array dimension size of
         the parent. 

       Remedy:
         Change the value in the idx1 and idx2 fields so that they represent
         a valid index into the parent array. 


10918  0-INFO VP2_REMOVE only one component 

       Cause:
         VP2_REMOVE currently supports the removal of one component. 

       Remedy:
         For now issue multiple VP2_REMOVEs or wait until it is implemented. 


10919  0-INFO VP2 Operation already in progress 

       Cause:
         Attempt to perform a VP2 operation eg. VP2_REMOVE whilst an
         operation is already active. 

       Remedy:
         Wait for the VP2 operation to complete. 


10920  0-INFO Error loading image 

       Cause:
         The specified image could not be loaded. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the image is correct type and supported by hardware. For
         example, .bmp is not supported by all Java machines. 


11083  0-INFO System variable is deprecated

         An attempt has been made to update a VP2 datalink which does not
         have a valid parent. 

       Remedy:
         If the datalink is added to an array of components, ensure that the
         indexes (idx_1 and/or idx_2) fields contain values within the array
         bounds.

11298  0-INFO Pipe full 

       Cause:

       Remedy:

       Remedy:

11300  0-INFO 


11301  0-INFO 


11302  0-INFO 


11303  0-INFO 


11304  0-INFO 


11305  0-INFO 


11306  0-INFO No pipe resources 

       Cause:
         If writing to a pipe, this indicates that the pipe already contains
         messages that have not yet been delivered and there is no room to
         write any more messages. If reading, this means there is already
         one or more programs waiting to read messages from the pipe and
         this request cannot be carried out. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the program that is on the other end of the pipe is
         active and is reading or writing data correctly. The input/output
         operation can also be retried after a time delay period. It is not
         recommended to repeatedly retry this operation, since this could
         cause the program to go into an indefinite loop. 


11307  0-INFO 


11308  0-INFO Not all files transferred 

       Cause:
         During a transfer of multiple files to the controller, one or more
         of the files could not be read because the file already exists on
         the controller and is a read-only or system file. 

       Remedy:
         Check the other messages that were displayed during the transfer to
         see which files were not transferred. If it is necessary to
         retransfer it, change its attributes first.

       Cause:

         to complete successfully. 

       Remedy:
         Check the other messages that were displayed during the transfer to
         see if any specific error was detected. Retry the operation.

11312  0-INFO File not found on PC 

       Cause:
         A file transfer between the controller and the attached PC failed
         because the requested file was not found on the PC. 

       Remedy:
         Move the file to the correct directory on the PC and make sure that
         it is available. 


11313  0-INFO File can not be created on PC 

       Cause:
         The file cannot be transferred from the controller to the PC
         because it cannot be created on the PC. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the default directory is valid on the PC. If a file
         of the same name exists on the PC, make sure that it is not set to
         read-only. 


11314  0-INFO File can not be deleted on PC 

       Cause:
         A file delete request from the controller to the PC cannot be
         completed. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the requested file on the PC is not set to
         read-only. 


11315  0-INFO File can not be renamed on PC 

       Cause:
         A file rename request from the controller to the PC cannot be
         completed. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that the requested file on the PC is not set to
         read-only. 


11316  0-INFO Error reading or writing file on PC 

       Cause:
         A fatal error was encountered on the PC while reading or writing
         the requested file. 

       Remedy:
         Check to see if the requested file on the PC is valid, and that the
         disk does not have any errors. 


11317  0-INFO PC disk is full 

       Cause:
         A file cannot be transferred from the controller to the PC because
         the PC's disk is full. 

       Remedy:
         Delete some files on the PC to make room for the new files. 


11318  0-INFO PC file transfer communications error 

       Cause:
         A file tranfer failed due to a communications error between the CRC
         and the PC. 

       Remedy:
         Check the connections and try the operation again. If it continues
         to fail, try using a lower baud rate.

         client. 

       Remedy:
         Please check the mail configuration parameters of the client.

       Remedy:
         Please check the syntax of the command.

         An unspecified network error occurred. 

       Remedy:
         Check the network status. 


11809  0-INFO Mail connection interrupted 

       Cause:
         A connection with a mail server was interrupted. 

       Remedy:
         Check the network and email server status. 


11810  0-INFO Mail from another CRC skipped 

       Cause:
         The automatic mail receiver, has received an email which appears to
         have already been replied to and is therefore ignored with no reply
         generated. The reason for this is that mails can become circular
         particular when there are alias email addresses or the same emails
         has been sent to many robots. The subject contains a mark to
         identify whether this email has already been handled. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the email server does not have multiple names for the
         same controller and check that the CC: field not contain other
         robots. 


11811  0-INFO Mail operation stopped because power failure in progress 

       Cause:
         A power failure is detected while a mail operation is in progress. 

       Remedy:
         Information only. 


11812  0-INFO Body or mail attachmnet too large 

       Cause:
         The received mail has body or attachment too large. 

       Remedy:
         If larger attachments can be received, increase the attachment
         size.

         The IP address is not correct. 

       Remedy:
         Please check the correctness of the inserted address.

       Remedy:
         Hardware reset the access point.

13339  10-DRIVE OFF DPRO timeout 

       Cause:
         A timeout occurred during the communication between the robot
         controller and the programming terminal. Possible causes:
         disconnection or restart of the terminal; terminal CPU overload
         (due, for example, to VP2 or JAVA resources). 

       Remedy:
         If the terminal has been disconnected or restarted (via further
         keys), this error is justified and should be ignored by the user.
         If the problem periodically occurs and always under the same
         conditions (for example running the same programs), try to optimize
         the use of VP2 or JAVA programs (if present). Check the hardware
         connections (TP cable or network cable which connects the docking
         station with the CPU). If the problem persists, please contact
         COMAU(service.robotics@comau.com).

13364  10-DRIVE OFF TP disconnected 

       Cause:
         An ethernet connection problem occurred in the communication
         between programming unit and controller. 

       Remedy:
         If the problem persist always in the same conditions (for example
         always with the same running programs), check that no PDL2 programs
         are overloading the CPU (for example programs with cycle loops
         without DELAY statements). If the problem persists, please contact
         COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com). 


13365  10-DRIVE OFF TP jog keys disconnected 

       Cause:
         An ethernet connection problem occurred when one or more keys  of
         the membrane keyboard are pressed  (for example during a jog
         operation of the robot). 

       Remedy:
         Please check the ethernet connection between the TP and the APC
         (connector positioned in the base of the robot, network cable
         inside the cabinet, etc...). If the problem persists , try to
         exchange this TP with another which never showed the problem, in
         order to understand if the problem is related to the TP or to the
         controller. If the system is equipped with a wireless cabinet, this
         message could indicate a bad reception of the radio signal, due for
         example to obstacles positioned between the terminal itself and the
         docking station. 


13366  10-DRIVE OFF KVC Timeout 

       Cause:
         An ethernet connection problem occurred when one or more keys  of
         the membrane keyboard are pressed  (for example during a jog
         operation of the robot). 

       Remedy:
         Please check the ethernet connection between the TP and the APC
         (connector positioned in the base of the robot, network cable
         inside the cabinet, etc...). If the problem persists , try to
         exchange this TP with another which never showed the problem, in
         order to understand if the problem is related to the TP or to the
         controller. If the system is equipped with a wireless cabinet, this
         message could indicate a bad reception of the radio signal, due for
         example to obstacles positioned between the terminal itself and the
         docking station. 


13367  2-WARNING KVC connection time expired 

       Cause:
         An ethernet connection problem occurred between the TP and the APC. 

       Remedy:
         Please check the ethernet connection between the TP and the APC
         (connector positioned in the base of the robot, network cable
         inside the cabinet, etc...). If the problem persists , try to
         exchange this TP with another which never showed the problem, in
         order to understand if the problem is related to the TP or to the
         controller. If the system is equipped with a wireless cabinet, this
         message could indicate a bad reception of the radio signal, due for
         example to obstacles positioned between the terminal itself and the
         docking station.

15368  0-INFO Data truncated

15369  0-INFO Data too long 

       Cause:
         The size of the data request for a write operation on an
         association is too long for the defined buffer size.  Or, on a
         connect request, the application relation name or server reference
         name is longer than the maximum allowable size. 

       Remedy:
         If the data request is too large, either shorten the length of the
         data or reconfigure the connection to use a larger buffer.  If
         making a connection request, specify valid names.

         correctly.

         communication parameters (parity, stop bits, etc..).

16390  4-PAUSE DV_CNTRL timed out 

       Cause:
         The requested asynchronous DV_CNTRL has timed out and therefore has
         not been completed. The system variable $DV_TOUT is used to set the
         timeout value with one such variable per system. 


16391  0-INFO 


16392  4-PAUSE Bad server index 

       Cause:
         The server index number supplied in the DV_CNTRL is not correct.
         Server numbers are from 1 to 16 and are returned in the DV_CNTRL
         when starting a server. 

       Remedy:
         Check the value supplied to the DV_CNTRL for starting, stopping or
         accessing the server.

16400  0-INFO No message 


16888  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: 


16889  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR:

17408  0-INFO Unimplemented feature 

       Cause:
         A feature used on the statement being translated is not yet
         implemented. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure proper software is loaded on the system.  It may be
         necessary to rework the program to avoid using the unimplemented
         feature. 


17409  0-INFO Invalid production offset 


17410  0-INFO Invalid production handle 


17411  0-INFO Invalid token 


17412  0-INFO Token stack overflow 


17413  0-INFO Ran out of local memory 

       Cause:
         The translation process ran out of free heap memory. 

       Remedy:
         There is a fixed amount of heap memory and it can't be changed by
         the user. 


17414  0-INFO Invalid data type used in an expression 

       Cause:
         An operand is an invalid data type.  For example, the NOT operator
         can only be applied on INTEGER and BOOLEAN operands.  An operand of
         any other data type will cause this error. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the operand(s) used in the expression. 


17415  0-INFO String value too long 

       Cause:
         A STRING literal exceeds the maximum length of 254. 

       Remedy:
         Use multiple shorter strings instead of one long string in the
         program. 


17416  0-INFO Invalid ASCII specification in a string value 

       Cause:
         An invalid ASCII specification has been detected in a STRING
         literal. This means a non-digit character is used in the 
nn
         notation or the number specified is not a valid ASCII character
         code.  For example, 'test 12a error' will cause this error since
         '12a' is not a valid 3 digit number. 

       Remedy:
         Use a proper 3 digit number in the 
nn notation of a STRING
         literal. 


17417  0-INFO BOOLEAN expression expected 

       Cause:
         The expression must result in a BOOLEAN value.  For example, "IF 5
         THEN" will cause this error since the expression for an IF
         statement must result in a BOOLEAN value. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the expression so it results in a BOOLEAN value. 


17418  0-INFO INTEGER expression expected 

       Cause:
         The expression must result in an INTEGER value.  For example "DELAY
         5.6" will cause this error since the expression for a DELAY
         statement must result in an INTEGER value. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the expression so it results in an INTEGER value. 


17419  0-INFO REAL expression expected 

       Cause:
         The expression must result in a REAL value.  If the expression
         results in an INTEGER value, it will be converted to a REAL
         automatically. However, if the expression results in any other data
         type, this error will be detected.  For example, "MOVE AWAY TRUE"
         will cause this error since the value of the expression is not
         INTEGER or REAL. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the expression so it results in a REAL value. 


17420  0-INFO VECTOR expression expected 

       Cause:
         The expression must result in a VECTOR value.  For example, "MOVE
         RELATIVE 5 IN BASE" will cause this error since 5 is not a valid
         VECTOR value. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the expression so it results in a VECTOR value. 


17421  0-INFO Positional typed expression expected 

       Cause:
         The expression must result in a POSITION, JOINTPOS, or XTNDPOS
         value. For example, "MOVE TO 6" will cause this error since the
         destination expression does not result in a POSITION, JOINTPOS, or
         XTNDPOS value. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the expression so it results in a POSITION, JOINTPOS, or
         XTNDPOS value. 


17422  0-INFO Invalid INTEGER operator 

       Cause:
         The operator cannot be used with INTEGER operands. For example, the
         "@" operator cannot have INTEGER operands. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the proper operands and operators are specified in the
         expression. 


17423  0-INFO Invalid REAL operator 

       Cause:
         The operator cannot be used with REAL operands. For example, the
         "@" operator cannot have REAL operands. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the proper operands and operators are specified in the
         expression. 


17424  0-INFO Invalid BOOLEAN operator 

       Cause:
         The operator cannot be used with BOOLEAN operands. For example, the
         "+" operator cannot have BOOLEAN operands. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the proper operands and operators are specified in the
         expression. 


17425  0-INFO Invalid STRING operator 

       Cause:
         The operator cannot be used with STRING operands. For example, the
         "+" operator cannot have STRING operands. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the proper operands and operators are specified in the
         expression. 


17426  0-INFO Invalid VECTOR operator 

       Cause:
         The operator cannot be used with VECTOR operands. For example, the
         "DIV" operator cannot have VECTOR operands. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the proper operands and operators are specified in the
         expression. 


17427  0-INFO Illegal statement context 

       Cause:
         A statement is used in the program in an invalid statement context.
         For example, all variable declarations must be in a VAR section and
         cannot appear between the BEGIN and END of the program.  If a VAR
         declaration is between the BEGIN and END this error will be
         detected. 

       Remedy:
         Move the statement to the proper context. 


17428  0-INFO Fields cannot be user-defined data types 

       Cause:
         A field of a record or node definition cannot be a record or node
         type. 

       Remedy:
         Rework the program to get around the requirement of having a field
         be a record or node type. 


17429  0-INFO Input file <file_name> not found 

       Cause:
         The file being translated does not exist. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the file name was properly entered. 


17430  0-INFO Error reading the input file 

       Cause:
         The FILER TRANSLATE command detected an error while reading the
         file being translated. 

       Remedy:
         This is an informational message. 


17431  0-INFO Error closing the input file 

       Cause:
         The FILER TRANSLATE command detected an error while closing the
         file being translated. 

       Remedy:
         This is an informational message. 


17432  0-INFO 


17433  0-INFO Identifier <id> undefined 

       Cause:
         An identifier is used in the statement which has not yet been
         declared. All identifiers used in a PDL2 program must be declared
         before any references to the identifiers are declared. 

       Remedy:
         Check spelling of the identifier to be sure it is the proper
         identifier to be used.  If so, add a proper declaration for the
         identifier. 


17434  0-INFO Id <id> must be an INTEGER constant 

       Cause:
         This error is detected when an identifier is used as the size of a
         STRING, ARRAY dimension, arm number, etc. and the identifier is not
         an INTEGER user-defined constant.  Only INTEGER user-defined
         constant identifiers can be used.  The following example would
         cause this error since "myvar" is a variable and not a user-defined
         constant. - -  VAR -    myvar : INTEGER -    s : STRING[myvar]  --
         Error since myvar is a variable 

       Remedy:
         Change the reference to a valid INTEGER user-defined constant or an
         INTEGER literal. 


17435  0-INFO Invalid STRING size 

       Cause:
         An invalid size was specified in a STRING declaration.  The size
         must be greater than 0 and less than the maximum size for a STRING
         which is 254.  For example, "VAR s : STRING[356]" would cause this
         error since 356 is too large. 

       Remedy:
         Change the size of the STRING to be in the range 1..254. 


17436  0-INFO Program name too long 

       Cause:
         The length of the specified program name is greater than 8. 

       Remedy:
         Shorten the length of the program name. 


17437  0-INFO Program identifier expected 

       Cause:
         A program identifier is expected but the translation process
         detected some other kind of identifier or literal.  For example, if
         "myvar" is declared as a variable, the "PAUSE myvar" statement
         would cause this error since "myvar" is not a program identifier. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the identifier referenced to be a program identifier. 


17438  0-INFO Identifier <id> previously declared 

       Cause:
         A user-defined identifier name can only be used once within the
         same scope.  For example, if the main program declares "myvar" as a
         variable, the name "myvar" cannot be used as the name of a routine,
         user-defined constant, user-defined type, or another variable
         declared in the main program. 

       Remedy:
         Choose a different name. 


17439  0-INFO Identifier not a record structure 

       Cause:
         A user-defined record type identifier is expected but the
         translation process detected some other kind of identifier.  The
         following example would cause this error since "myvar" is not a
         user-defined RECORD type identifier. - -  VAR -    myvar : INTEGER
         -    recvar : myvar  -- Error since myvar is a variable 

       Remedy:
         Fix the identifier referenced to be a user-defined record type
         identifier. 


17440  0-INFO Invalid target in an assignment statement 

       Cause:
         This error occurs due to an invalid left operand of the assignment
         statement.  The left operand must be a valid variable, parameter,
         or local variable reference. For example, "5 := a" will cause this
         error since "5" is not a valid variable identifier reference. 

       Remedy:
         Fix the left operand of the assignment statement to be a valid
         variable, parameter, or local variable reference. 


17441  0-INFO Data type mismatch in assignment statement 

       Cause:
         The data type of the right operand of an assignment statement is
         not compatible with the left operand variable reference.  The left
         and right operands must be of the exact same data type with the
         exception that the right operand can be INTEGER if the left is
         REAL.  The following example will cause this error to occur since
         6.7 is REAL and incompatible with an INTEGER variable. - -  VAR -  
         myvar : INTEGER -    yourvar : REAL -  . . . -  BEGIN -    -- Valid
         statement (can assign INTEGER to REAL) -    yourvar := myvar - -   
         -- Invalid statement (can't assign REAL to INTEGER) -    myvar :=
         6.7 

       Remedy:
         Fix the assignment statement so the operands are compatible data
         types. 


17442  0-INFO Assignment not permitted on variables of this type 

       Cause:
         Not all variables can be assigned a value using the assignment
         statement.  This error is the result of trying to perform an
         assignment to a variable whose data type is not permitted.  For
         example, if "myvar" is declared as a SEMAPHORE variable, it cannot
         be used as the left operand in the assignment statement ("myvar :=
         ..."). 


17443  0-INFO Ran out of memory 

       Cause:
         The translation process ran out of free memory. 

       Remedy:
         Erase all unnecessary programs and variables from memory and
         retranslate.  If the error was detected while editing a program,
         suspend from the editor to perform the erasing so previous changes
         to the program are not lost. 


17444  0-INFO Implicitly declaring variable <var_id>
