         The time must be specified using the format HH:MM:SS, where HH
         means Hours (00-24), MM means Minutes (00-59), and SS means Seconds
         (00-59). 


22608  0-INFO Bad date format 

       Cause:
         An incorrect date was specified. 

       Remedy:
         The date must be specified using the format YY-MM-DD, where DD
         means Day (01-31), MM means Month (01-12), and YY means Year
         (00-99). 


22609  0-INFO Bad year format 

       Cause:
         An incorrect year was specified.  The year must be specified using
         a two character format. For example, 1991 must be expressed as 91. 


22610  0-INFO 


22611  0-INFO 


22612  0-INFO 


22613  0-INFO Disabled due to cmnd conflict 

       Cause:
         The command cannot be executed because it is in mutual exclusion
         with another currently active command. If an edit environment is
         being entered (IDE, ProgramEdit or MemoryDebug), please check that
         no other programming environments are open. Please note that this
         error can occur also in case the IDE page is open but no program is
         viewed. 

       Remedy:
         Wait until the command in mutual exclusion is completed. 


22614  0-INFO 


22615  0-INFO Operation not completed 

       Cause:
         The operation did not complete successfully and the user replied
         negative to the confirmation. 

       Remedy:
         This is an informational message. 


22616  0-INFO 


22617  0-INFO Cannot rename on different device 

       Cause:
         The RENAME operation is allowed only on the same device. 


22618  0-INFO Kind of print not allowed 

       Cause:
         The PRINT command is not allowed between the source and destination
         devices specified. 


22619  0-INFO Cannot open output stream 

       Cause:
         The operation is not executed either because the device was not
         found or the limit of possible files opened was already reached. 

       Remedy:
         Check the device connection, the serial line cable, and the port
         characteristics. Close an opened file. 


22620  0-INFO Bad port name 

       Cause:
         The device specified is not a correct port name.  Check the use of
         the ':' at the end of the device name. 


22621  0-INFO Port type not allowed 

       Cause:
         The specified port is not correct for the required operation. 

       Remedy:
         Check the port name.  Correct ports are $DIN, $DOUT, $AIN, $AOUT,
         $GI, $GO, $SDI, $SDO. 


22622  0-INFO Ambiguous or bad value 

       Cause:
         The index or the forced value of the port is not correct. 

       Remedy:
         Be sure the index value is within the valid range for the current
         I/O configuration and a forced value is valid for the specified
         kind of port. 


22623  0-INFO No memory for this operation 

       Cause:
         There is not enough memory for executing the command. 

       Remedy:
         Remove unused programs and variables from execution memory (use the
         MEMORY ERASE group of commands). If not sufficient, check the
         system configuration of memory resources. 


22624  0-INFO 


22625  0-INFO 


22626  0-INFO 


22627  0-INFO 


22628  0-INFO 


22629  0-INFO 


22630  0-INFO 


22631  0-INFO 


22632  0-INFO 


22633  0-INFO Bad window name 

       Cause:
         The specified string does not correspond to a window name. 


22634  0-INFO Bad board index 

       Cause:
         The specified index board is not present in the system. 


22635  0-INFO Holdable stmt only in PROG 

       Cause:
         The EXECUTE (E) command was issued with holdable statements (LOCK,
         UNLOCK, RESUME, MOVE, CANCEL, etc..), but the state of the system
         was not PROG. 

       Remedy:
         Change the OP/TP switches to PROG. 


22636  0-INFO Bad stmt for immediate mode 

       Cause:
         The statement specified as parameter in the EXECUTE (E) command is
         not allowed. For example, DISABLE/ENABLE/PURGE CONDITION would
         cause this error. 


22637  0-INFO Immediate execution not allowed 

       Cause:
         Execution of the EXECUTE (E) command is not compatible with the
         state of the system. For example, this error would occur when the
         state of the system is changed from PROG to AUTO when the EXECUTE
         of a holdable statement is currently active. 

       Remedy:
         Check that the state of the system is not changed when executing a
         holdable statement. 


22638  0-INFO 


22639  0-INFO Bad numerical value 

       Cause:
         A numeric parameter includes a non-numeric character (e.g., 12c3). 

       Remedy:
         Check the input parameter 


22640  0-INFO Bad $GEN_OVR value 

       Cause:
         The value specified is not in the allowed range (1-100). 


22641  0-INFO Bad $TP_GEN_INCR value 

       Cause:
         The value specified is not in the allowed range (1-10). 


22642  0-INFO Varfile name conflict 

       Cause:
         The PROGRAM GO (PG) command was issued for a program already loaded
         in memory, with the variable values loaded from a variable file
         with a different name than the program. 

       Remedy:
         Use the PROGRAM ACTIVATE (PA) command to start the current
         situation, or use the MEMORY ERASE VARIABLE (MEV) command and then
         PROGRAM GO (PG) to start the new configuration (with the variable
         file name the same as the program name). 


22643  0-INFO File extension required 

       Cause:
         This command requires the extension of the file specification. A
         default is not assumed. 


22644  0-INFO Bad device operation 

       Cause:
         The specified device cannot be used for this kind of operation. 


22645  0-INFO Source file must be binary 

       Cause:
         Only binary files (for example .COD, .BKC, .VAR, or .BKV,...)can be
         used as source file in a print (FP) operation from UD: to UD:. 


22646  0-INFO Destination file cannot be binary 

       Cause:
         A binary file ( e.g. .COD, .BKC, .VAR, or .BKV, ...) cannot be used
         as destination in a print (FP) operation from UD: to UD:. 


22647  0-INFO 


22648  0-INFO Program not activated 

       Cause:
         The PROGRAM ACTIVATE (PA) command was issued, but the program
         cannot be activated. The reason for the failure is reported on the
         scroll window of the TP or CRT (or on $SYS_CALL_OUT in case of
         SYS_CALL). 


22649  0-INFO Missing variable name 

       Cause:
         The command requires a variable name parameter, but the variable
         name was not specified. For example, the MEMORY ERASE VARIABLE
         (MEV) command requires a variable name parameter. 

       Remedy:
         Re-issue the command specifying the variable name. In most cases,
         the wildcard (*) is allowed. 


22650  0-INFO Command not done for all programs 

       Cause:
         A command acting on multiple programs was issued, but the operation
         failed for some of the programs. The reason for the failure is
         reported on the scroll window of the TP or CRT (or on $SYS_CALL_OUT
         in case of SYS_CALL). 

       Remedy:
         Determine the reason for the failure and take the appropriate
         remedy action. 


22651  0-INFO No application event defined 

       Cause:
         The UTILITY APPLICATION (UA) command was issued, but there was no
         application event (AC_CALL_CRT, AC_CALL_TP) enabled at the time. 
         Refer to the "Condition Handlers" chapter of the PDL2 Language
         Manual for more detailed information. 

       Remedy:
         Before issuing the command, create and activate a program that
         defines and enables conditions, for example: - -  CONDITION[1]: -  
         WHEN EVENT AC_CALL_CRT DO -    . . . -  ENDCONDITION -    . . . - 
         ENABLE CONDITION[1] 


22652  0-INFO Invalid password 

       Cause:
         The password specified for the CONFIGURE CNTRLER PASSWORD (CCP)
         command is not valid. 


22653  0-INFO Not enough access rights 

       Cause:
         The user that is logged in the controller does not have enough
         access rights for executing this command. 

       Remedy:
         Please login again (SET LOGIN coomand) with a username and a
         password related to a user profile previously defined (CONFIGURE
         CONTOLLER LOGIN ADD) that allows the operation to be accomplished. 


22654  0-INFO Disabled due to DRIVE ON state 

       Cause:
         This command can be executed only when in the DRIVE OFF state. 


22655  0-INFO Disabled due to DRIVE OFF state 

       Cause:
         This command can be executed only when in the DRIVE ON state. 


22656  0-INFO Disabled due to HOLD system state 

       Cause:
         This command cannot be executed in the HOLD state. 


22657  0-INFO Disabled due to AUTO system state 

       Cause:
         This command cannot be executed in the AUTO state. 


22658  0-INFO Disabled due to FATAL system state 

       Cause:
         This command cannot be executed in the FATAL state. 


22659  0-INFO Stmt not bypassed in all programs 

       Cause:
         The PROGRAM STATE BYPASS (PSB) command was issued for more than one
         program, but the operation failed for some program. 

       Remedy:
         Determine the cause of the failure and take the appropriate remedy
         action. 


22660  0-INFO Not supported option 


22661  0-INFO Cannot increase $GEN_OVR 

       Cause:
         It is not possible to increase the value of $GEN_OVR from a program
         (SYS_CALL) or from a remote process for security reasons. In these
         cases $GEN_OVR can only be decreased in value. 

       Remedy:
         If the $GEN_OVR value needs to be incremented, the user can press
         the TP appropriate keys or can issue the command SET ARM GEN_OVR
         (SAG) from the keyboard (if the Teach Pendant is disconnected) or
         from the Teach Pendant command menus. 


22662  0-INFO Too many options 

       Cause:
         Too many options were specified in the command. For example,
         issuing a PROGRAM ACTIVATE /CYCLE /MOVE command (PA/C/M) would
         return this error. 

       Remedy:
         Re-issue the command specifying the correct number of options. 


22663  0-INFO /List requires /Back and .COD 

       Cause:
         Returned when issuing a FILER TRANSLATE /LIST (FT/L) without also
         specifying the /BACK option.  The listing can be obtained only when
         translating from a .COD to a .PDL file, so the FILER TRANSLATE (FT)
         should be executed with the /BACK option. Otherwise, the effect
         would be to translate from a .PDL to a .COD and the listing could
         not be created. The listing is not allowed on a .VAR or .LSV file. 

       Remedy:
         Re-issue the command with the correct options. 


22664  0-INFO Not all files translated 

       Cause:
         The FILER TRANSLATE (FT) command was issued for more than one
         program but the operation failed for some programs. The reason for
         the failure is reported on the scroll window of the TP or CRT (or
         on $SYS_CALL_OUT in case of SYS_CALL). 

       Remedy:
         Determine the reason for the failure and take the appropriate
         remedy action. 


22665  0-INFO Arm number required 


22666  0-INFO Disabled due to TP out of cabinet 

       Cause:
         This command cannot be executed when the teach pendant (TP) is
         connected and out of cabinet. This limitation is linked to safety
         reasons. 

       Remedy:
         Insert the teach pnedant in the controller cabinet before issuing
         the command again. 


22667  0-INFO Not enough space for pop-up window 

       Cause:
         The pop-up window cannot appear on the screen because there is not
         enough space. 

       Remedy:
         Remove some other pop-up windows before re-issuing the command. 


22668  0-INFO Disabled due to remote state 

       Cause:
         This command cannot be executed because the controller is in a
         remote state. 

       Remedy:
         Change the controller status to execute the command. 


22669  0-INFO Bad baud rate value 

       Cause:
         The specified baud rate value is not in the range of allowed
         values. 

       Remedy:
         Use one of the allowed values (110, 300, 1200, 2400, 4800, 9600,
         19200, 38400). 


22670  0-INFO Field not present in this path 

       Cause:
         The specified field has not been declared as belonging to the path
         node. 

       Remedy:
         If the field is needed, add it to the NODEDEF declaration for the
         path. 


22671  0-INFO Not a path type variable 

       Cause:
         This error happens when trying to insert a node on a variable type
         different than path. 

       Remedy:
         Check for the correctness of the operations. 


22672  0-INFO Bad arm number for this path 

       Cause:
         This error happens when trying to insert a node or modifying the
         $MAIN_POS for a node belonging to a path variable using a different
         arm than the one declared in the node structure. 

       Remedy:
         Use the arm declared in the node structure for that path variable. 


22673  0-INFO Cannot insert. Check state selector 

       Cause:
         The REC or the MOD key has been pressed on the TP. The action
         cannot be executed because the system state is not in the right
         condition. Teaching is only permitted in PROG state. 

       Remedy:
         Put the controller in PROG state. Check the current state on the
         system screen in the upper window (system window.) 


22674  0-INFO Cannot delete. Check state selector 

       Cause:
         The DEL key has been pressed on the TP. The action cannot be
         executed because the system state is not in the right condition.
         Deletion is only permitted in PROG state. 

       Remedy:
         Put the controller in PROG state. Check the current state on the
         system screen in the upper window (system window.) 


22675  0-INFO Cannot modify. Bad var type 

       Cause:
         The MOD key has been pressed on the TP. The action cannot be
         executed because the current variable data type is not allowed in
         this operation. You can only modify single data type variable at a
         time (not arrays or path variable type). 


22676  0-INFO Wrong node index 

       Cause:
         You are trying to modify a field of a path node with a bad node
         index value. 

       Remedy:
         Check the node index value and the current number of nodes for that
         path. 


22677  0-INFO Cannot modify. Check state selector 


22678  0-INFO Prog must be loaded with /FULL opt 


22679  0-INFO 


22680  0-INFO String not found 


22681  0-INFO Disabled by another programming environment 

       Cause:
         The command is not enabled due to the fact that another programming
         environment is active. 

       Remedy:
         Enter such environment or exit from it before issuing the command
         again. 


22682  0-INFO Invalid file type 


22683  2-WARNING Program not modified 


22684  2-WARNING Cannot enable an arm in SIMULATE mode

22686  0-INFO 


22687  2-WARNING Log file %s has been lost 

       Cause:
         Log files are in sequence and one of them has been lost. 

       Remedy:
         This is just an informational message. 


22688  2-WARNING Error reading log file %s. Error: %d 

       Cause:
         The log file could not be read due to the reported error. 

       Remedy:
         Check with the reported error. 


22689  2-WARNING Insufficient logs recorded. Display <number> 

       Cause:
         Requested a large number of error logs than exists. 

       Remedy:
         This is just an informational message. 


22690  2-WARNING No log files found 

       Cause:
         No log files could be found. 

       Remedy:
         Verify that log files have been created. 


22691  0-INFO Non all files undeleted 

       Cause:
         Not all the files were undeleted. 


22692  0-INFO Insufficient login rights 

       Cause:
         Attempt to issue a command when have insufficient login rights. 

       Remedy:
         Login to the controller with sufficient rights. 


22693  0-INFO Bad or missing saveset file 

       Cause:
         The saveset has not been specified for the file or is badly formed. 

       Remedy:
         Must specify a save set option and check the syntax. 


22694  0-INFO Command currently not available 

       Cause:
         The specified command is not available. 

       Remedy:
         Wait for a next software version. 


22695  2-WARNING Warning: less than <number> Kbytes free on disk <disk> 

       Cause:
         The disk is becoming full. 

       Remedy:
         Cleanup the disk. 


22696  0-INFO No users defined 

       Cause:
         No users defined in the database. 

       Remedy:
         This is just an informational message. 


22697  0-INFO Invalid password 

       Cause:
         The specified password is not valid. 

       Remedy:
         Check that it contains an alpha-numeric character. 


22698  0-INFO Login failed 

       Cause:
         Unable to login either due to invalid user identifier or password. 

       Remedy:
         Check the user identifier and password. 


22699  2-WARNING No user logged 

       Cause:
         Attempt to logout when no user logged in. 

       Remedy:
         This is just an informational message. 


22700  0-INFO Exclusive login 

       Cause:
         Login has failed as the current user on the controller has
         exclusive login rights. This disallowes the usage of the controller
         from a different device that the one this exclusive user is using. 

       Remedy:
         Logout from all devices connected to the controller. Eventually
         clear the startup login. 


22701  2-WARNING Calibration file set to: %s 

       Cause:
         $SYS_ID system variable is not properly set. Therefore it was not
         possible to assign a standard name to the calibration file. 

       Remedy:
         Properly set the $SYS_ID value. Issue the command again. 


22702  0-INFO No latched alarms 

       Cause:
         There are currently no latched alarms active. 

       Remedy:
         This is just an informational message. 


22703  2-WARNING Jog keys unavailable when using Jpad 

       Cause:
         Jog keys not available when pressing a JPad key. 

       Remedy:
         Do not press both at same time. 


22704  2-WARNING Jpad unavailable when using Jog keys 

       Cause:
         Jpad keys not available when pressing a Jog key. 

       Remedy:
         Do not press both at same time. 


22705  2-WARNING Insufficient rights for changing $GEN_OVR 

       Cause:
         Insufficient access rights for changing the general override. 

       Remedy:
         Login with sufficient rights. 


22706  2-WARNING Insufficient rights for Jogging the robot 

       Cause:
         Insufficient rights for jogging the robot. 

       Remedy:
         Login with sufficient rights. 


22707  0-INFO Insufficient rights for I/O port modification 

       Cause:
         The user is logged in the controller with access right that are not
         sufficient for changing this I/O port. 

       Remedy:
         Login with a profile that has these rights. 


22708  0-INFO System file name not allowed 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to perform a partial save of the system
         (ConfigureSaveCategory) into a filename which is the same as the
         system. 

       Remedy:
         Provide an alternative name. 


22709  0-INFO Resource not existing 

       Cause:
         A command has been sent to a not existing PLC resource. 

       Remedy:
         Please provide a different name, check that the syntax is correct
         and that the resource belongs to the current project. 


22710  0-INFO Command to the resource failed 

       Cause:
         An error occurred upon a command sent to the resource. 

       Remedy:
         Usually another error message is displayed on the system window
         which indicates the origin of the problem. 


22711  2-WARNING IDE opened, cannot change the arm 

       Cause:
         Cannot change the arm when IDE is opened. 

       Remedy:
         Close IDE before changing the arm. 


22712  0-INFO Phone number needs to be supplied 

       Cause:
         When trying to remote connect over a modem need to specify a phone
         number. 

       Remedy:
         Issue the command supplying a phone number. 


22713  0-INFO Mismatch between memory and disk 

       Cause:
         The Restart operation detected a mismatch between programs in
         memory and the related files on the disk. 

       Remedy:
         Check which programs have not been saved for detecting the
         disalignement in respect to the execution memory. For avoiding this
         check, please set bit 20 of $CNTRL_CNFG to 1. 


22714  4-PAUSE Timeout: command not executed 

       Cause:
         The requested operation failed due to the timeout of the maximum
         time foreseen for its completion. 

       Remedy:
         Issue the command again and if a user operation need to be done,
         please perform it within the maximum 


22715  0-INFO User database commands disabled 

       Cause:
         The $CNTRL_CNFG bit has been set which disables the manipulation of
         the user database. 

       Remedy:
         Download a new file or remove the bit. 


22716  0-INFO File contains no Property/Comment 

       Cause:
         The file does not contain Property/Comments. 


22717  2-WARNING Jog keys unavailable when using MGD 

       Cause:
         Jog keys not available when using the Manual Guidance Device. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use jog keys while using Manual Guidance Device for jogging. 


22718  2-WARNING Jpad keys unavailable when using MGD 

       Cause:
         Jpad keys not available when using the Manual Guidance Device. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use jpad keys while using Manual Guidance Device for
         jogging. 


22719  2-WARNING Press enabling device or activate MGD from Motion page 

       Cause:
         You are trying to jog with MGD device while the robot is drive off
         or MGD has not been previously enabled from the Motion page of the
         TP. 

       Remedy:
         Press the enabling device in order to drive on the robot or enable
         the jogging with MGD from the Motion page of the TP. 


22720  2-WARNING MGD movement unavailable when using Jog keys 

       Cause:
         The movement with MGD is unavailable when the robot is moved with
         Jog keys. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use Manual Guidance Device while using Jog keys. 


22721  2-WARNING MGD movement unavailable when using Jpad keys 

       Cause:
         The movement with MGD is unavailable when the robot is moved with
         Jpad keys. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use Manual Guidance Device while using Jpad keys. 


22722  0-INFO Operation incompleted. View action log for details 

       Cause:
         The operation did not complete successfully. The information on the
         failure has been placed in the log file. 

       Remedy:
         Check which is the cause of the failure and act accordingly. 


22723  0-INFO Attempt to login using user group 

       Cause:
         Attempting to login using a user group and not a specific user. 

       Remedy:
         Login using a userid. 


22724  0-INFO Not valid group name specified 

       Cause:
         Attempting to create a User group but the name is not valid. 

       Remedy:
         Verify the name provided. 


22725  0-INFO Output command failed 

       Cause:
         The use of the option /Output failed. 

       Remedy:
         Check the name of the output specified is legal, disk not full,
         etc.. 


22726  0-INFO Protection rights not changed on all files 

       Cause:
         The  command used for adding or removing protection to a file was
         not successful on all of them. 

       Remedy:

22727  0-INFO Remote interface is not available 

       Cause:
         The command has no effect because no actions or events are
         configured. 

       Remedy:
         This is an informational messsage. 


22728  0-INFO Comando not available in ALARM state 

       Cause:
         The command is not executable when the system is in ALARM state Non
         si pu eseguire il comando in quanto il sistema si trova nello
         stato ALARM. 

       Remedy:

23552  0-INFO 


23555  8-HOLD Power contactor %s of the package %s is not open.Waiting %s 

       Cause:
         The welding remote control switch has been instructed to open, but
         the input that detects the remote control switch status does not
         feature the opening value. The message shows the input expected
         status 

       Remedy:
         Check the welding remote control functioning. Make sure the remote
         control switch status is received properly 


23556  8-HOLD Power contactor %s of the package %s is not closed.Waiting
       %s 

       Cause:
         The welding remote control switch has been instructed to close, but
         the input that detects the remote control switch status does not
         feature the closing value. The message shows the input expected
         status 

       Remedy:
         Check the welding remote control functioning. Make sure the remote
         control switch status is received properly 


23557  8-HOLD Power contactor %s of the package %s, incorrect command : %s
        %s 

       Cause:
         The remote control switch status changed, without the
         opening/closing command changing. The message shows the command
         status and the input expected status 

       Remedy:
         Check the welding remote control functioning. Make sure the remote
         control switch status is received properly 


23558  8-HOLD No air pressure package %s $IN[%s]=%s 

       Cause:
         The air circuit pressure control detected insufficient pressure 

       Remedy:
         Check the air circuit feeding. Check the manostat functioning. Make
         sure the manostat status is received properly. 


23559  8-HOLD No water flow package %s Flux %s %s 

       Cause:
         IThe water circuit flow control detected an insufficient flow 

       Remedy:
         Check the air circuit feeding. Check the flowmeters functioning.
         Make sure the flowmters status is received properly. 


23560  8-HOLD No water pressure package %s %s %s 

       Cause:
         The water circuit pressure control detected insufficient pressure 

       Remedy:
         Check the air circuit feeding. Check the manostat functioning. Make
         sure the manostat status is received properly. 


23561  8-HOLD Water flow present without command pack %s Flux %s %s 

       Cause:
         The water circuit flow control detects a flow, despite the Shut-Off
         solenoid valve has been instructed to interrupt the hydraulic
         circuit. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the input for flow present has not been forced, neither
         in terms of logic OR electronics. Check the flowmeters functioning.
         Make sure the flowmters status is received properly. 


23562  8-HOLD Welding timer %s not ready 

       Cause:
         The welding timer is not ready for the welding procedure 

       Remedy:
         Check if the welding time is faulty. Make sure the timer is
         suitably powered 


23563  8-HOLD Welding main circuit breaker %s OPEN 

       Cause:
         The welding main switch is open 

       Remedy:
         Close the welding main switch 


23564  8-HOLD Mismatch %s weld yes/no timer state/command 

       Cause:
         The weld yes/no command echo from the timer does not correspond to
         the command 

       Remedy:
         Check if the welding timer is faulty. 


23565  8-HOLD Timeout end of welding timer %s 

       Cause:
         The welding end signal from the timer has not been delivered within
         the time set 

       Remedy:
         Check from timer, if events occur, that hindered the timer response
         to the welding command, (end of electrode life duration, etc.) and
         act correspondingly 


23566  8-HOLD Welding timer %s ALARM 


23567  8-HOLD Weld parameter outside limits timer %s. (%s - %s) [%s] 

       Cause:
         The welding program or the spot index is outside the permissible
         range. The message shows the permissible range. 

       Remedy:
         Correct the welding instruction, entering a value within the range 


23568  8-HOLD Timer: %s Weld_par %s not managed 

       Cause:
         The welding timer can' t manage the received welding parameter type
         (weld_prog, spot index, spot table, ...) 

       Remedy:
         Relate to Comau the error and the right timer's welding parameter 


23569  8-HOLD Gun %s not open $DIN[%s]=OFF 

       Cause:
         Open gun signal missing. The alarms arises at a gun_open
         technological instruction, if the open gun status is not detected
         within the time set 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure AND there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is open, check the open gun sensor. Make
         sure the sensor signal is received properly. 


23570  8-HOLD Gun %s still totally open $DIN[%s]= ON 

       Cause:
         The gun remained fully open. The alarm arises by a gun_open
         technological instruction, if the the fully open gun signal stays
         in the ON status. 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure and there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is open, make sure the open gun sensor has
         not been forced or is experiencing a short circuit. Make sure the
         sensor signal is received properly. 


23571  8-HOLD Gun %s not closed $DIN[%s]= OFF 

       Cause:
         Closed gun signal missing. The alarm arises by the welding
         performing, if the gun closed status is not detected after the
         closing instruction 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure AND there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is closed, check the closed gun sensor. Make
         sure the sensor signal is received properly. 


23572  8-HOLD Gun %s still closed $DIN[%s]=ON 

       Cause:
         The gun remained closed. The alarm arises at the end of a welding
         procedure, if the closed gun signal stays in the ON status after an
         open gun instruction has been sent. 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure AND there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is open, make sure the open gun sensor has
         not been forced or is experiencing a short circuit. Make sure the
         sensor signal is received properly. 


23573  8-HOLD Gun %s still open $DIN[%s]=ON 

       Cause:
         The gun remained open. The alarm arises by the carrying out of a
         gun_open_retract technological instruction or during a welding
         procedure, if the open gun signal stays in the ON status. 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure and there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is open, make sure the open gun sensor has
         not been forced or is experiencing a short circuit. Make sure the
         sensor signal is received properly. 


23574  8-HOLD %s gun retract not open $DIN[%s]=OFF 

       Cause:
         The gun remained open. The alarm arises by the carrying out of a
         gun_open_retract technological instruction, if the fully open gun
         status is not detected within the time set 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If the gun did not move, make sure the
         command reaches the solenoid valve. Make sure the pneumatic system
         is supplied with sufficient pressure and there are no mechanical
         hindrances. If the gun is fully open, check the fully open gun
         sensor. Make sure the sensor signal is received properly 


23575  8-HOLD Gun %s Transformer temperature/flow switch fault $DIN[%s]=%s 

       Cause:
         The gun transformer thermostat signals that the operating
         temperature is too high 

       Remedy:
         Make sure the sensor signal is received properly. Check the cooling
         water flow and/or the average welding current used during the cycle 


23576  8-HOLD %s timer index already used for other ARM. Weld init not
       valid 

       Cause:
         A weld_init or spot_init instruction for the timer specified has
         alredy been performed by a program related to a different ARM. 

       Remedy:
         Assign a different timer to each ARM 


23577  8-HOLD Unknown welding result internal code(%s) 


23578  10-DRIVE OFF Unknown internal status code(%s) 


23579  4-PAUSE Unknown FAULT_CODE internal code (%s) 


23580  4-PAUSE Timer %s Alarm: %s 

       Cause:
         The welding timer detected a fault during welding. The message
         feature the timer ALARM number and the corresponding text. 

       Remedy:
         The action depends on the type of fault detected. Refer to the
         usage and maintenance manual of the timer installed. 


23581  4-PAUSE SmartSpot: routine spot_init not executed 

       Cause:
         SmartSpot: the routine spot_init has not been executed 

       Remedy:
         Run the SmartSpot routine spot_init 


23582  4-PAUSE Inputs/Outputs Index outside limit. (1 - %s) (Input
       /Output) 

       Cause:
         The routine dari_get_opt_in, to read the SWIM card optional inputs
         status, has been called using a number of inputs higher that the
         maximum one 

       Remedy:
         Correct the intrction entering a permissible value 


23583  8-HOLD End of welding input = ON before weld START 

       Cause:
         The welding end signal coming from the timer is alredy ON, at the
         time when the welding command is issued 

       Remedy:
         Check if the welding timer is faulty 


23584  8-HOLD Gun %s status unknown 

       Cause:
         It is not possible to is open or fully open. The alarm refers to
         gun supplier with pre-stroke. and arises during the welding
         carrying out. Before the closing instruction, the gun status is
         checked in order to instruct the pre-stroke suitably 

       Remedy:
         Check the gun position. If it is open or fully open, check the
         sensors and make sure the signals are received properly 


23585  8-HOLD Gun %s open sensor mulfunction 

       Cause:
         The open gun input stays in the ON status by closed gun as well 

       Remedy:
         Check the open gun sensor. Make sure it has not been forced or is
         experiencing a short circuit. Make sure that when the gun is closed
         on the plate, the sensor is not engaged. Adjust the sensor position
         suitably

         routine sw_check_swingarm_work_1 doesn't return TRUE when the arm
         is in work position 


23682  8-HOLD Tip dresser swingarm not in home position 

       Cause:
         The Tip dresser swingarm has been controlled in home position but
         the home position was not detected within the timeout. This alarm
         is also raised if the swingarm home position is not detected in the
         beginning of the cycle. 

       Remedy:
         Check the swingarm home position sensors. Verify why the user
         routine sw_check_swingarm_home_1 doesn't return TRUE when the arm
         is in home position

         is displayed the application package stops the activation

         reconfigurations and the application become effective

         This is displayed after a system restart and signifies that the
         application is ready to operate

23994  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC START FAILURE 

       Cause:
         D 

       Remedy:
         Check the parameters set on the welder for the welding program
         selected; Check the hardware connections between C4G and welder;
         Check all conditions that could determine bad welder functioning. 


23995  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC STOP FAILURE 

       Cause:
         Displayed after an off command, if the arc does not cut out within
         the time of 'Time_2'. After performing the checks indicated in
         Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         check the hardware connections between C5G and welder; check all
         conditions that could determine bad welder functioning 


23996  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) $GEN_OVR LESS THAN 100%% 

       Cause:
         Displayed after an ignition command or during the weld-yes process,
         if the C5G $GEN_OVR is not set at max. value (100%). After
         performing the checks indicated in Remedy, send an alarm reset
         command. 

       Remedy:
         Check the value of $GEN_OVR on C5G. 


23997  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) POWER SOURCE NOT READY (ERROR CODE PWS
       %s) 

       Cause:
         Displayed after an On command or during the weld-yes process, if
         the welder PWS1 (singol modality if welder twin model) is in alarm
         condition. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy, send an
         alarm reset command. NOTE: For detailed documentation on the error
         codes of this device, see the manufacturer's manual Robot Interface
         - Operating Instructions. 

       Remedy:
         check the hardware connection between C5G and welder; check all
         conditions that could determine bad welder functioning. 


23998  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC STOP 

       Cause:
         Displayed a during the weld-yes process, if the arc remains off
         longer than the time set with 'Time_7'. After performing the checks
         indicated in Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         check the parameters set on the welder for the selected welding
         program; check hardware connections between C5G and welder. 


23999  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) WIRE STUCK 

       Cause:
         Displayed after an arc off command, if the wire is found stuck to
         the weld bead. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy,
         send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Perform an alarm reset to carry out an automatic burning of the
         wire, or cut the wire by hand; Check the parameters set on the
         welder regarding wire burning (if managed); Check hardware
         connections between C5G and welder. 


24000  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC_PROG: PARAMETERS OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the parameter in the ARC_PROG is out of range. After
         performing the checks indicated in Remedy, send an alarm reset
         command. 

       Remedy:
         Change the parameter received and repeat the instruction. 


24001  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC_JOB: PARAMETERS OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the parameter contained in the ARC_JOB instruction is
         out of the correct range. After performing the checks indicated in
         Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Change the parameter and repeat the instruction. 


24002  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) WELDING PARAMETERS OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if a welding table is used (called with ARC_START or
         ARC_TBCHx) that has one or more parameters with values out of the
         correct range. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy,
         send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Check and change the value of the parameters relating to the
         welding table used and perform an alarm reset. 


24003  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) PROTECTED CONDITION USED 

       Cause:
         Displayed if a shielded condition is used (numbered from 175 to
         235) in the user program. The move program moves automatically at
         the alarm reset. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy,
         send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Change the move program and reactivate it. 


24004  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) A_WEAVE: PARAMETERS OVER LIMIT

         Displayed if the parameter sent in the A_WEAVE instruction is out
         of the correct range. After performing the checks indicated in
         Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Change the parameter sent and repeat the instruction.

         alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:

24006  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC STARTED 

       Cause:
         Appears after a command switch, when the bow is already running.
         After performing the checks in Remedy, send a reset command
         allarme. 

       Remedy:
         Check the hardware connections between C5G and welder; Check all
         conditions that may cause the malfunction of welder. 


24007  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) SPEED PARAMETER OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if a welding table is used (called with ARC_START or
         ARC_CHxx) that has a SPEED parameter with a value higher than the
         maximum limit set in SETUP (parameter SET_1). After performing the
         checks indicated in Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Check and change the value of the SPEED parameter in the welding
         table used. 


24008  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ARC_START: PARAMETER OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the parameter sent in the ARC_START instruction is out
         of the correct range. After performing the checks indicated in
         Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Change the parameters sent and repeat the instruction. 


24009  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) NO WELDING GAS FLOW 

       Cause:
         Displayed after an On command or during the weld-yes process,
         should the gas flow present signal be missing. After performing the
         checks indicated in Remedy, send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Check the presence and proper functioning of the gas flow sensor
         (if present); Check that the gas is present and that the flow rate
         is that required by the process; If the gas flow sensor is not
         present, disable the control of the signal (SETUP, parameter
         Enbl_2). 


24010  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) WELDING NOT ALLOWED (ERROR CODE %s) 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the welding process cannot be resumed because the
         robot position has been lost during a welding process (either in
         weld-yes or in weld-no). This situation occurs when the user aborts
         a move between an arc on instruction and an arc off instruction. To
         resume the movement an alarm reset command is necessary. ERROR code
         <1>: POS out of range <2>: process MOVE at slow speed <3>: process
         MOVE deleted by CANCEL <4>: process MOVE deleted by ^C or BYPASS
         <5> : process MOVE delated by the forced trajectory on the final
         spot <6> : process inhibition due to syncmove spot modification 

       Remedy:
         Wait for the move in progress to finish. The ARC_END instruction
         will restore normal operating conditions. 


24011  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) ALARM FROM EXTERNAL SENSOR 

       Cause:
         G 


24012  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) POWER SOURCE UNIT IN LOCAL STATE 

       Cause:
         Some welders have a selector switch that permits the welder to
         accept process commands from the local panel or from an external
         device (C5G). Displayed after an On command or during the weld-yes
         process, if the selector switch on the welder is in LOCAL mode.
         After performing the checks indicated in Remedy, send an alarm
         reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Check the local/remote selector switch state on the welder panel
         (if present) and set it to REMOTE. 


24013  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) S_ARC_START: <POS> PARAMETER NOT
       ASSIGNED 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the POS parameter of the S_ARC_START instruction has
         not been assigned. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy,
         send an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Assign a value to the POS parameter and repeat the instruction. 


24014  4-PAUSE (SmartArc - ARM[%s]) S_ARC_START: <POS> DISTANCE OVER LIMIT 

       Cause:
         Displayed if the position assigned to the POS parameter of the
         S_ARC_START instruction has a distance that is over the allowed
         limit of 50 mm, in relation to the arc ignition point with
         S_ARC_START. After performing the checks indicated in Remedy, send
         an alarm reset command. 

       Remedy:
         Bring the position assigned to the POS parameter within the allowed
         range and repeat the instruction.

       allowed with selected search pattern

         in WSF setup.

         Change search pattern in WSF setup or don't use SearchPattern('3D',
         ...).

24576  2-WARNING Program <prog_id> started 

       Cause:
         Indicates the startup program, specified in $STARTUP, was started. 

       Remedy:
         This is an informational message and requires no user remedy. 


24577  2-WARNING Program <program_name> not started <error_num> 

       Cause:
         Indicates the startup program was not activated. The error number
         reported in this message is the cause of the failure of the
         activation. 

       Remedy:
         Check the error corresponding to the number reported with this
         message. For example: "STARTUP program not started 22563" indicates
         error number 22563 which is "File .cod not found". 


24578  2-WARNING STARTUP program <prog_id>. Press START 

       Cause:
         Indicates the startup program was activated. Being a holdable
         program, it also requires the START button be pressed. 


24579  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL bad char in cmnd 

       Cause:
         Indicates a non alphanumeric character is specified in the command
         string of the SYS_CALL. The command string of the SYS_CALL is the
         first parameter to provide to the SYS_CALL. The following example
         would cause this error since the "_" is non alphabetic: - - 
         SYS_CALL ('_i', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         The command string of the SYS_CALL can only contain alphanumeric
         characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9). Check which is the correct string
         corresponding to the desired command. 


24580  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL bad cmnd 

       Cause:
         Indicates a nonexisting command is specified in the command string
         (first parameter) of the SYS_CALL. The following example would
         cause this error since the MEMORY VIEW (MV) menu does not include a
         K command. - -  SYS_CALL('mvk', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check which is the correct string corresponding to the desired
         command. 


24581  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL too few char in cmnd 

       Cause:
         Indicates the command string (first parameter) in the SYS_CALL
         contains too few characters for the command identification. The
         following example would cause this error since FILER (F) is not a
         complete command: - -  SYS_CALL('f', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check and modify the first parameter to the SYS_CALL. 


24582  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL too many char in cmnd 

       Cause:
         Indicates the command string (first parameter) in the SYS_CALL
         contains too many characters for the command identification. The
         following example would cause this error since the FILER COPY (FC)
         command does not have any submenus: - -  SYS_CALL('fcgh', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check and modify the first parameter to the SYS_CALL. 


24583  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL cmnd not available 

       Cause:
         Indicates a command already present on the command menu but not yet
         implemented is specified in the command string of the SYS_CALL. 

       Remedy:
         Do not use unimplemented commands as parameters to SYS_CALL. 


24584  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL command not allowed 

       Cause:
         Indicates a command that cannot be executed from SYS_CALL is
         specified in the command string of SYS_CALL. The following example
         would cause this error since PROGRAM EDIT (PE) is not permitted
         from SYS_CALL: - -  SYS_CALL('PE', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check which are the commands not allowed from SYS_CALL and do not
         use them. 


24585  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL bad number of parameters 

       Cause:
         Indicates the number of parameters given to the SYS_CALL is not
         what is expected for that command. The following example would
         cause this error as the name of the label on which the breakpoint
         should be set is not specified: - -  SYS_CALL('ptbi/l', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check which is the correct number of parameters needed for a
         certain command and specify them as parameters of the SYS_CALL. 


24586  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL bad option specified 

       Cause:
         Indicates an unexpected option for a certain command is specified
         in the SYS_CALL. The following example would cause this error as K
         is not a valid option for the PROGRAM VIEW (PV) command. - - 
         SYS_CALL('PV/K', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Check which are the expected options for the desired command. An
         easy way for checking this is to issue the option key (/) for the
         command on the CRT/TP.  When issued, a menu of possible options for
         the command is displayed. 


24587  4-PAUSE SYS_CALL no options allowed 

       Cause:
         Indicates an option is specified in the command string when the
         command does not expect any. The following example would cause this
         error as the PROGRAM TEST STEP CYCLE (PTSC) command does not have
         any options: - -  SYS_CALL('PTSC/F', 'pippo') 

       Remedy:
         Remove the option specification from the command string: in the
         example above the correct statement is: - -  SYS_CALL('PTSC',
         'pippo'). 


24588  4-PAUSE No Command session available 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to open a Command request but non is available. 

       Remedy:
         Make sure that all outstanding command sessions have been closed. 


24589  4-PAUSE Request already active 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to issue a command on a session that already
         has a command oustanding. 

       Remedy:
         Wait until the existing command completes. 


24590  4-PAUSE Missing technology value 

       Cause:
         The CCLA/T has been issued but with no technology value. 

       Remedy:
         Call with a user technology value. 


24591  2-WARNING Executing of <program_name> failed <error_num> 

       Cause:
         EPL_GEN program did not start  or returned an error. 


24592  4-PAUSE Missing the output filename 

       Cause:
         The /Output option has been specified but no file could be found. 

       Remedy:
         The last parameter when using /Output must be the filename for the
         output. 


24593  0-INFO 


25081  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Invalid ISPT instance 


25082  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Instance limit reached:%d 


25083  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Unknown CL packet received 


25084  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Invalid CL session identifier 


25085  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Invalid CL reply received 


25086  0-INFO SYSTEM ERROR: Received unknown packet type:%d

25600  2-WARNING Bad $TUNE[1], set <value> cond scan 

       Cause:
         A value out of range is assigned to the variable $TUNE[1]
         containing the Condition Handler scanning time. The correct range
         is from 10 to 5000 milliseconds. For example, "$TUNE[1] := 6000"
         would cause this warning to be displayed. 

       Remedy:
         No remedy is needed as the system automatically changes the value
         of $TUNE[1] to the default value (20 milliseconds). 


25601  2-WARNING <prog_id> cond <cond_num> has been redefined 

       Cause:
         A condition is defined more than once. The following example shows
         a situation in which this warning would be returned: - -  PROGRAM a
         -  BEGIN -    CONDITION[1]: -      WHEN HOLD DO -        $FDOUT[5]
         := ON -    ENDCONDITION -    . . . -    . . . -    -- Execution of
         the next statement will -    --   cause the error if the
         condition[1] was -    --   not previously purged. -   
         CONDITION[1]: -      WHEN START DO -        $FDOUT[5] := OFF -   
         ENDCONDITION -    . . . -  END a - In the above example,
         CONDITION[1] is defined twice. The warning is given when the second
         definition is executed. Note that only the last definition is
         considered, so in the example above the event monitored will be the
         START and not the HOLD. 

       Remedy:
         No action is necessary. This is only a warning. It is up to the
         user to decide if a certain condition is to be redefined at a
         certain point of the program or if this warning indicates a
         programming error. 


25602  2-WARNING <prog_id> cond <cond_num> already enabled 

       Cause:
         An enabling operation is performed on a condition and the condition
         is already enabled. The following example could cause such a
         warning when the condition triggers: - -  CONDITION[3] NODISABLE: -
         WHEN HOLD DO -      ENABLE CONDITION[3] -  ENDCONDITION - In fact,
         the NODISABLE clause allows the condition to remain enabled when it
         triggers; so the ENABLE action has no meaning in this context and
         would cause the warning to be returned. Another case is when the
         condition contains motion events and the condition is enabled both
         globally and locally. In this case the condition may trigger at the
         wrong motion segment. In particular, this can happen when the
         global condition is also locally enabled for a MOVEFLY .. ADVANCE
         and the condition expression is AT END. It is recommended that the
         same condition or type of condition event should not be used
         globally and locally at the same time. 

       Remedy:
         No action is necessary, this is only a warning. The user should
         decide if the situation is correct or if this warning indicates a
         programming error. 


25603  2-WARNING <prog_id> cond <cond_num> already disabled 

       Cause:
         A disabling operation is performed on a condition and the condition
         is in fact already disabled. 

       Remedy:
         No action is necessary, this is only a warning. It is up to the
         user to decide if the situation is correct or if this warning
         indicates a programming error. 


25604  8-HOLD Cond <cond_num> not found 

       Cause:
         A condition that does not exist is referenced in a statement.  The
         following example will cause this error since the condition was
         purged (deleted) right before it is used in the ENABLE statement: -
         -  . . . -  BEGIN -    . . . -    PURGE CONDITION[1] -    ENABLE
         CONDITION[1] 

       Remedy:
         Check the reason why the condition is not present (e.g., not
         defined, purged, etc.). 


25605  4-PAUSE Cond used locally 

       Cause:
         An attempt was made to purge a condition while the condition was
         locally used. For example, if CONDITION[2] in the following program
         segment triggers during the MOVE, this error could occur since
         CONDITION[1] is locally enabled on the MOVE and the action of
         CONDITION[2] is to purge it: - -  VAR p1 : POSITION -  . . . - 
         BEGIN -    . . . -    CONDITION [1]: -      . . . -    ENDCONDITION
         -    CONDITION [2]: -      WHEN $DIN[1]+ DO -        PURGE
         CONDITION[1] -    ENDCONDITION -    ENABLE CONDITION[2] -    --
         CONDITION[1] is locally enabled in -    --   the following
         statement -    MOVE TO p1 WITH CONDITION[1] 

       Remedy:
         Check the PURGE CONDITION statement use. This statement should be
         executed when the condition being purged is not locally enabled. 


25606  8-HOLD No memory resources for cond 

       Cause:
         The operations to be performed for handling conditions requires the
         use of memory. This error indicates there is not sufficient memory. 

       Remedy:
         Check the configuration of the memory and/or remove something from
         memory. 


25607  12-DRIVE OFF No CPU resources for cond 

       Cause:
         This error can occur when bad condition handler programming methods
         are used. Usually this happens when the actions of one condition
         handler trigger the execution of another condition handler or when
         a condition is continuously enabled, by either an ENABLE CONDITION
         statement or the NODISABLE attribute. The actions that can cause
         this problem are: the program actions (ACTIVATE, PAUSE, etc..), the
         routine call action, the RESUME action, and the SIGNAL and CANCEL
         of semaphore actions. These actions use a lot of CPU time, and
         therefore should be used in conditions that do not trigger every
         scan. 

       Remedy:
         Check if there are programs running with condition handlers written
         as described above.  Change those conditions to use less CPU time. 
         For example, if possible make the state condition an event
         condition, or remove the NODISABLE attribute and enable the
         condition only when it is strictly needed. If, on the contrary,
         there are programming mistakes contact COMAU
         (service.robotics@comau.com).

26633  2-WARNING Failure <error_num> reading <port_num> port image 

       Cause:
         There are one or more I/O points (ports) in conditions that are not
         present. 

       Remedy:
         Check to see if there are some programs running with conditions and
         if the ports affected by the conditions are present.  Probably due
         to an I/O configuration, these ports are no longer mapped or are
         mapped with a different index.  The failure number can help
         you--search for this number in the standard error. 


26634  14-FATAL Failure <error_num> in $TIMER allocation 

       Cause:
         There is not enough system memory to allocate all required timers,
         probably due to a large value for $NUM_TIMERS. 

       Remedy:
         Reduce the $NUM_TIMERS value to the minimum required in your
         application.

26646  2-WARNING Event $<port_name>[<port_num>]<transition> triggers too
       fast 

       Cause:
         The value of a port changes too frequently. Due to system overload
         it is not guaranteed that all the flips are detected. This occurs
         for example if a $DIN passes from 1 to 0 and to 1 again in a time
         interval of 30 milliseconds. 

       Remedy:
         Change the I/O event on that port in a I/O state condition.

         reports a code that identifies the memory area that could not be
         allocated.

       Cause:
         The hardware test failed. 

       Remedy:
         Replace the system board.

       Cause:
         The hardware test detected an error in RAM memory (local or
         shared). 

       Remedy:
         Replace the system board. 


28674  15-FATAL No response from CPU <board_name> 

       Cause:
         The hardware test failed during diagnostic handshake with the board
         containing the microprocessor. 

       Remedy:
         Replace the system board and/or the other CPU board. 


28675  14-FATAL Aborted task <task_name> 

       Cause:
         A task is stopped by the operating system due to an unrecoverable
         error. 

       Remedy:
         Restart the system software by powering off the electronics of the
         controller. Issue a Backup using the Saveset Srv and contatact
         COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com).

         WATCHDOG circuit detected a software malfunction.

         require the use of memory. This error indicates there is not
         sufficient memory. 

       Remedy:

         memory.

28711  10-DRIVE OFF START failure, STS: <status_bits> 

       Cause:
         The system board cannot correctly complete the START procedure. 

       Remedy:
         Try resetting the system. If the problem persists, please contact
         COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com) and refer the error parameter. 


28712  10-DRIVE OFF HOLD failure, STS:<status_bits> 

       Cause:
         The system board cannot complete the HOLD procedure correctly. 

       Remedy:
         Try resetting the system. If the problem persists, please contact
         COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com) and refer the error parameter. 


28713  10-DRIVE OFF No answer from servo board during <command_type>
       command (phase:<number>) 

       Cause:
         An anomaly has been detected during DRIVE-ON / OFF. 

       Remedy:
         Re-issue the command or reset the system. If the problem persists,
         please contact COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com)providing the
         parameters associated to the error. 


28714  10-DRIVE OFF Machine Status Selector fault,
       STS:<PROG_T2_bit><PROG_T1_bit><AUTO_L_bit><AUTO_R_bit> 

       Cause:
         The PROGR/AUTO switch on the control panel does not work correctly.
         There is more than one signal at the same time.  This means that
         the switch position is ambiguous. 

       Remedy:
         Check the PROGR/AUTO switch or connection with the control panel
         electronic board. 


28715  2-WARNING $TUNE[<index>] value out of range 

       Cause:
         One or more elements of $TUNE has an invalid value. 

       Remedy:
         Check the manual for the valid range or check the .C5G file. 


28716  2-WARNING Arm <arm_num> not calibrated 

       Cause:
         Motion was started on an arm that is not calibrated. 

       Remedy:
         Try to recover the calibration data before running the calibration
         tool. Check to see if the arm should be calibrated or the
         calibration data can be loaded from the NVRAM. 


28717  2-WARNING HOLD from PDL2 statement 

       Cause:
         One of the PDL2 programs sent a HOLD command to the system. 

       Remedy:
         Release the HOLD by pressing the HOLD button on control panel or
         the teach pendant. 


28718  2-WARNING Release the Enabling Device on TP 

       Cause:
         This message is issued when the system enters the DRIVE-OFF
         condition and the enabling device is pressed. 

       Remedy:
         Release the enabling device before issuing the DRIVE-ON again. 


28719  2-WARNING TP presence switch on 

       Cause:
         The TP Enabling Device switch was pressed while the TP is on the
         cabinet. This is also a safety test for revealed TP presence switch
         malfunction. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the TP from the cabinet if you want to use a MANUAL MOTION
         feature that requires the Enabling Device switch or check if the TP
         presence switch is working correctly. 


28720  2-WARNING DRIVE ON not allowed in ALARM state 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request in ALARM state. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the ALARM before pressing the DRIVE ON button. 


28721  0-INFO 


28722  2-WARNING DRIVE ON allowed from TP only 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request when the state selector was
         positioned on PROG-T1, AUTO-T or AUTO-L. 

       Remedy:
         Use the DRIVE ON button on the teach pendant while the state
         selector is in PROG-T1 or switch the state selector on AUTO-R and 
         re-issue the command from remote. 


28723  0-INFO 


28724  2-WARNING DRIVE ON allowed from REMOTE only 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request from the teach pendant when
         the state selector is in AUTO-R. 

       Remedy:
         In AUTO-R issue the DRIVE ON signal from the remote device. 


28725  2-WARNING START not allowed in ALARM state 

       Cause:
         The system received a START request in ALARM state. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the ALARM before issuing the START request. 


28726  2-WARNING START not allowed in HOLD state 

       Cause:
         The system received a starting request (START) during the HOLD
         state. This HOLD condition could be forced in case the user did not
         execute yet the requested operation that is viewed on the status
         window. 

       Remedy:
         Remove the HOLD condition before issuing the START command. 


28727  2-WARNING START allowed from TP only 

       Cause:
         The system received a remote START request but the state selector
         is positioned on PROG-T1, PROG-T2 or AUTO-L. 

       Remedy:
         If the START should be issued from remote, switch the state
         selector to AUTO-R else press the START button on the teach
         pendant.

       Cause:
         The system received a START request with the PROGR/AUTO switch in
         the AUTO-R position. 

       Remedy:
         Issue the START request from the remote device. 


28730  2-WARNING No arm enabled for DRIVE ON 

       Cause:
         All arms are disabled, you cannot issue a DRIVE ON request for a
         disabled arm. 

       Remedy:
         Enable the arms before pressing the DRIVE ON button.

         disabled.

28737  13-FATAL Power failure recovery failed, board <board_num> 

       Cause:
         The indicated board did not complete the power failure recovery
         procedure and did not reply. 

       Remedy:
         Check the board or the physical conditions of the arm. Check the
         presence of the physical connection between drives and boards.
         Check the state of the leds of the drives. 


28738  2-WARNING DRIVE OFF due to arm changed in PROG 

       Cause:
         Arm selection changed while DRIVE ON.  Only the arm selected can be
         in DRIVE ON.  In PROG, the system switches the previous arm to
         DRIVE OFF.

28747  2-WARNING DRIVE ON not allowed on disabled arm <arm_num> 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request for a disabled arm. 

       Remedy:

28748  2-WARNING START with arm <arm_num> in DRIVE OFF 

       Cause:
         The system received a START request when the drives were switched
         off (DRIVE OFF). In presence of rotating tables, this message
         derives from the request of switching the table on, which includes
         an implicit START. 

       Remedy:
         The START command is only allowed in case the robot is able to
         move. Perform a DRIVE ON before a START.

28750  0-INFO 


28751  2-WARNING DRIVE ON not allowed with FIELDBUS DRIVE OFF 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON command with the NOT DRIVE OFF
         request active from remote. 

       Remedy:
         Please check that remote commands have been activated with the
         proper sequence. In case it is needed, in a system state different
         from REMOTE, to switch in DRIVE ON, issue the SetInputRemoteDisable
         command. In this way the remote interface is temporarely disabled
         until the next system state change or until the next
         SetInputRemoteEnable command.

       Remedy:

         The START button on the teach pendant must be  pressed after the
         enabling device. 

       Remedy:
         Release the START button and press it again after the enabling
         device pressure. If the problem persists, check that the START
         button is working.

       Cause:
         The BACK button on the teach pendant must be pressed after the
         enabling device. 

       Remedy:

         button is working.

         Jog buttons on the teach pendant must be pressed after the enabling

       Remedy:

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request during a DRIVE OFF
         procedure. 

       Remedy:
         Wait until DRIVE OFF procedure completes, then reissue the DRIVE ON
         request. 


28767  2-WARNING DRIVE ON not allowed without enabling device 

       Cause:
         The system received a DRIVE ON request when the enabling device was
         released. When working in PROG or AUTO-T, the enabling device must
         be pressed before the DRIVE ON button. 

       Remedy:
         Use the DRIVE ON button after having pressed the enabling device on
         the teach pendant.

28774  2-WARNING Power failure recovery completed 

       Cause:
         The controller had completed the recovery phase due to a power
         failure. 

       Remedy:

         from this situation. 


28775  0-INFO [<time>] received <command> remote command from <source>
       board 

       Cause:
         The controller received a command from one of the REMOTE devices.
         This message is used as a trace of the REMOTE commands received on
         the robot controller from a PLC or HOST COMPUTER. The possible
         commands are: DRIVE-ON, DRIVE-OFF, START, and HOLD. 


28776  2-WARNING Remove <local_command> for entering the AUTO-R

       Cause:
         The EXCL key present on the teach pendant (TP) can only be used
         when the state of the controller is PROG. 

       Remedy:
         Please check the position of the state selector to be on PROG-T1.

       Cause:

         REMOTE although NOT DRIVE OFF and NOT HOLD remote signals are not
         active.

28780  2-WARNING Remote signals are enabled

         Remote signals are re-enabled. 

       Remedy:

28782  2-WARNING SHIFT-ARM allowed with DRIVE-OFF only 

       Cause:
         The SHIFT-ARM TP key pressure is only enabled when the controller
         is in DRIVE-OFF state. 

       Remedy:

         SHIFT-ARM key. 


28783  2-WARNING Rotating table: command refused on arm%d due to DRIVE-OFF
       state 

       Cause:
         Cannot start the Motor On procedure on this rotating table due to
         the DRIVE-OFF state of the system. 

       Remedy:
         The system must be in DRIVE-ON 


28784  2-WARNING Rotating table: command refused on arm%d due to PROG
       state 

       Cause:
         Cannot start the Motor On procedure on this rotating table due to
         the PROG state of the system. 

       Remedy:
         The Motor On procedure cannot be started if the system is in PROG
         state. 


28785  1-INFO Rotating table: DRIVE-OFF due to safety open inputs 

       Cause:
         The system has the safety inputs of the rotating table open. In
         this situation, the motors cannot be switched on. 

       Remedy:
         In order to switch the motors on, the safety contacts must be
         closed on one or more rotating tables. 


28786  2-WARNING Shutdown recovery completed 

       Cause:
         The controller had completed the recovery phase due to a Shutdown
         command. 

       Remedy:
         This alarm notifies about the Shutdown command and the recovery
         from this situation.

28796  2-WARNING BACK with arm <arm_num> in DRIVE OFF 

       Cause:
         The system received a BACK request with DRIVE OFF status. 

       Remedy:
         The BACK is allowed only when the robot can move.  Issue a DRIVE ON
         request before the BACK. 


28797  2-WARNING START/BACK allowed while EDIT or Execute active 

       Cause:
         The system received a START or a BACK request, in PROG state, when
         the EDIT or the Execute command were not active. 

       Remedy:
         The START or BACK are allowed when an EDIT session or the Execute
         command are active. These functions are used in PROG state to
         enable the motion after a move instruction has been issued to the
         system. 


28798  2-WARNING Arm <arm_num> needs a Turn Set operation 

       Cause:
         It is not possible to execute MOVE instructions when the arm needs
         the turn-set operation. 

       Remedy:
         Turn-set the arm before executing MOVE instructions. 


28799  2-WARNING AUX_SET: not configured option 

       Cause:
         An AUX_SET built-in was issued on a system not configured for this
         option. 

       Remedy:
         The AUX_SET built-in is only allowed on specific configurations of
         robots having auxiliary axes. Check if the configuration is correct
         or, if needed, ask for a new configuration file. 


28800  2-WARNING AUX_SET built-in in progress 

       Cause:
         You are requesting a command that is not allowed during the
         execution of the AUX_SET PDL2 built-in. Possible commands that are
         not allowed contemporarely to the AUX_SET built-in are: DRIVE ON or
         another AUX_SET or AUX_DRIVES built-in. 

       Remedy:
         Wait for the completion of the first command before issuing again
         the refused one. If needed, try to syncronize those processes that
         could cause the contemporaneus issuing of commands. 


28801  2-WARNING AUX_SET not allowed during other commands 

       Cause:
         An AUX_SET built-in has been issued from a PDL2 program meanwhile
         another incompatible command on motors was in progress. The AUX_SET
         built-in cannot be executed while one of the following procedures
         is in progress: DRIVE ON and DRIVE OFF commands, activation and
         deactivation of "energy saving" state, power failure recovery. 

       Remedy:
         Issue again the AUX_SET built-in when no other incompatible command
         is in progress. Try to synchronize the program that executes the
         AUX_SET built-in with processes that issue the other commands. 


28802  10-DRIVE OFF AUX_SET: procedure <procedure name> failed
       (phase:<number> err:<error_num>) 

       Cause:
         The system board cannot correctly complete the AUX_SET built-in
         execution. 

       Remedy:
         Check the situation and contact COMAU (service.robotics@comau.com). 


28803  0-INFO 


28804  0-INFO 


28805  0-INFO 


28806  10-DRIVE OFF Signals from safety board change too fast 

       Cause:
         The system software reads signals coming from the safety board at
         least every 10 ms. In case these signals change too frequently, the
         system is not able to execute commands coming from safeties. 

       Remedy:
         Check the link to the safety board or devices. 


28807  10-DRIVE OFF Signals from remote change too fast 

       Cause:
         The system software reads signals coming from remote at least every
         10 ms. In case these signals change too frequently, the system is
         not able to execute commands coming from external devices. 

       Remedy:
         Checks the link to the board of remote signals or to the source of
         the signals (CAN, PLC,..). 


28808  11-DRIVE OFF Safety gate 

       Cause:
         Inputs 47 ($SDI[47]) and 48 ($SDI[48]), or both, on the safety
         board are low.  This means that the safety gate is open. 

       Remedy:
         Close the safety gate in order ro enable DRIVE ON. 


28809  0-INFO 


28810  0-INFO 


28811  11-DRIVE OFF General stop 

       Cause:
         Input 43 ($SDI[43]) or  44 ($SDI[44]) or both on safety board are
         low. This means that the associated safety contact have been
         opened. 

       Remedy:
         Check and close the contacts that allow the stop for enabling the
         DRIVE ON.
